\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 CHAPTER I \f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-250\slmult0\qc\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\b\scaps\f0\fs18 Markel\b0\scaps0 , the Lekthwan, occupied a strange and beautiful dwelling on the highest crag of Mount Whitney, consisting of six domes, three minarets, and a wide terrace. The domes were formed of almost clear crystal, the minarets were white porcelain-stuff, the surrounding terrace was blue glass, and in turn was surrounded by a rococo balustrade with blue and white spiral stanchions.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 To Earther minds, Markel was like his dwelling\emdash beautiful, incomprehensible, disturbing. His skin shone lustrous gold; his features were fine, hard, exotic in their spacing. He wore soft black garments: tight breeches, sandals resting on two inches of air, a cloak which fell into dramatic shapes apparently of its own volition.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Markel welcomed no strangers, made no appointments, but contrived to conduct a large volume of business with small effort. He employed a dozen agents, conferring daily with each via Lekthwan three-dimensional television, which produced the illusion of face-to-face discussion. He occasionally flew abroad in his air-boat, occasionally received visitors from other Lekthwan domes.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 His two Earther attendants, Claude Darran and Roy Barch, found him formal, courteous, painfully patient. Some of their duties were familiar enough, with parallels from their own experience: washing down the terrace, polishing the air-boat; others involved apparently irrational operations. When they made mistakes, Markel repeated his instructions, while Darran and Barch reacted each to his temperament\emdash Darran ruefully apologetic, Barch listening with grim concentration.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel's psychological attitude was perhaps as much due to preoccupation as any innate conviction of superiority. On occasion he extended himself to be gracious. Noticing a mark on Barch's chin, he asked, "How did you do that?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Cut myself shaving," said Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel's eyebrows flickered in surprise. He entered the dome, returning a few minutes later with a flask of clear liquid. "Wipe this over your face and you'll never need to shave again."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked dubiously at the bottle. "I've heard of stuff like this. It takes your face along with the beard."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel shook his head politely. "You need not worry in this case." He turned away, then paused. "A ship will be arriving today; my family will be aboard. We will receive them formally at eleven o'clock. Is that clear?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Very well," said Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You understand the landing operation?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Perfectly," said Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel nodded, continued around the terrace, the space under his sandals giving him a springing, striding gait. Barch went to the quarters he shared with Darran, cautiously applied the depilatory to his face. When he felt his cheeks, the stubble had disappeared.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran came in. "There's going to be a shake-up. The old man's family is arriving today\emdash a wife and two daughters. Now everybody toes the mark, Markel included."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch nodded. "I know. He asked me if I remembered how to fold down the balustrade. Also, he said 'formal'\emdash  that means monkey suits." He glanced sourly at his skintight green coveralls with the blue jacket. "I feel like a ballet dancer in that outfit." He handed Darran the bottle. "Here, make yourself beautiful. It's depilatory, removes your beard\emdash a present from Markel. If we had ten gallons, we'd be millionaires."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran weighed the flask in his hand. "Some kind of hint? Maybe we're looking seedy."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "If it was deodorant, I might think so."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran looked at his wrist watch. "Ten-thirty; we'd better get into our uniforms."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 When they arrived at the landing stage, Markel already stood by the balustrade. He inspected them briefly, then, pulling the peak-visored cap lower over his eyes, turned to look out over the panorama to the south.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Moments passed. Down from the sky floated a glistening ball, striped red, gold, blue and silver. It expanded swiftly, the stripes flashing and whirling. Barch and Darran bent over the balustrade, felt for the locks. The balustrade collapsed into the blue glass, and a blast of cold air blew across the terrace.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The space-ball loomed overhead like a mountain, the stripes boiling and melting like the colors of a soap bubble. It pressed close, locked to the terrace.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The hull broke open into an arched portal. Markel stood like a statue; Barch and Darran stared.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Five Lekthwans came forth: two women, two men, and a little girl who ran gaily across the terrace. Markel cried out a greeting, lifted the child high with one golden arm, with the other embraced the two women. There were a few moments of staccato Lekthwan conversation, then Markel set down the child, led the party into the near rotunda.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 From the portal slid a dozen crates, cushioned on two inches of air, like Markel's sandals. Barch and Darran guided them one at a time to the service dome.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The portal closed, the colors in the hull boiled furiously. The space-ball drifted back from the landing stage, spun off into the east.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran and Barch, left alone on the terrace, watched it dwindle to a spot of color.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Well, that's that," said Darran. "Now we've seen the big shot's family." He waited, but Barch made no comment. They lifted the balustrade back into place. "The older woman must be his wife," Darran went on reflectively, "and the two girls, his daughters."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Cute little kid," said Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran turned him a quizzical glance. "How about the other one?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch bent over a crate. "Why argue? She's beautiful." He glanced briefly toward the rotunda. "But she's still something off another planet, strange as a fish."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran shrugged. "We're making a good thing out of those 'fish.' They pay through the nose for everything we sell them. They've advanced us hundreds of years. We're building spaceships with principles of science we never even dreamed of. We've cut the death rate with their medicine\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's not our science, nor our medicine."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It works, doesn't it?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It never grew on Earth; it's not good transplanting that alien stuff."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran regarded him curiously. "If you don't like the Lekthwans how come you're up here working for Markel?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch turned him a speculative glance. "I could ask you the same question."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'm here because I might learn something."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch abruptly turned away. "Guys like you are too easygoing. You want to be nice."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Sure. It's nice to be nice."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Are the Lekthwans nice to you? Maybe they come down to visit your house, buy you a beer?" Barch snorted. "Not on your life. They're Lekthwans; we're the peasants."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Give them time," said Darran. "They're a long way ahead, we're strangers to each other. They're decent enough\emdash maybe a little stand-offish."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch's bright hazel eyes glittered like coals. "And in a few years\emdash what then? We were doing pretty well as Earthers, making progress every year. Homegrown, native, natural progress. Do you know what's going to happen to us? In those few more years you talk about, we'll be through. We won't be any good as Lekthwans\emdash they won't have us\emdash and we'll be a hell of a lot worse as Earthers."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You'll never win a prize for optimism," said Darran. He bent over a crate, gave it a shove toward the door. "Let's be realistic. The Lekthwans are here. We can't turn back the clock. Why should we want to? We've got a lot to gain."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Only what they decide is good for us."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran shook his head. "Earthers at Lekthwan schools learn anything they want to."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "First you've got to know the language."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran laughed. "Do you expect them to run their schools in English?" Darran laughed cheerfully. "You're looking through the wrong end of the telescope. Maybe you ought to go to visit their planet. It might give you a different slant."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "If I go to Lekthwa, I'll go to learn something pretty basic, and that's how to ease these gold-plate snobs off of Earth."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tkz Maerkl-Elaksd\emdash Markel, as the Earthers called him\emdash  awaiting his wife Tcher, his daughters Komeitk Lelianr and Sia Spedz, stood looking through the wall of his south salon across the great California deserts. He wore no cloak; afternoon sunlight coppered the gold of his skin.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Behind him sounded the quick pad of feet; Sia Spedz came running out barefoot, wearing a diaphane diaper with white pompons at each hip. Her hair was finest platinum floss, burnished and waxed, parted in the middle, flared playfully over each ear. She stood on tiptoe by the wall looking out over the view. "Where are the other domes? Are we all alone?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel stroked her head. "No, there are agencies all around Earth."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And always on the mountain tops?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yes, that's how we secure isolation and privacy." He turned as his wife and his second daughter appeared, wearing simple white kirtles. Tcher, the mother, dressed her hair sleek as a silver cap against her head. Komeitk Lelianr, the daughter, combed hers into a high tuft, like a silver flame.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel brought forth couches of half-living white foam. "And your voyage, was it pleasant?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr grimaced. Tcher said, "Everywhere but at Great Dark Cloud. A Klau web forced us to stop."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel stirred uneasily in his seat. "And then?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "A boat clamped alongside, intending to send aboard a search party."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "But why? Why?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We were told that a dozen Lenape escaped from Magarak and the Klau would not have them win back to Lenau."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, that would be a great defeat for the Klau," Markel murmured. "And then?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The ship master behaved with enormous dignity. He commenced a sight and sound broadcast of the Klau anxiety, and in five minutes they withdrew."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel conveyed his understanding through the complex Lekthwan eyebrow, eye and eyelash mood-language, and by the same method indicated a change in subject. He turned to Sia Spedz: "Tell me, how goes your gain of life-experience?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The girl wriggled her toes. "Everyone commends my ability. I have learned eleven characterizations and three optionals, which are: Smiling Sunrise, Playful Kitten and The Solitary One."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Excellent."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tcher said with whimsical pride, "She can walk twenty feet high on her sandals, and she went alone out around Mirska Moon in a day-boat."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "On Earth she must be more cautious," said Markel. "Lekthwans are not universally popular."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Sia Spedz asked in puzzlement, "Why is that? Do we not help them, do we not train them at our Lekthwan schools?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel smiled quietly. "The Earthers have long considered themselves unique in the universe, and the coming of the Lekthwans has been a blow to their pride."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Sia Spedz continued doubtfully. "Also I know all the Lekthwan reigns, dynasties and realms, starting with King Phalder in the proto-history."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Down on the plains of Earth, you will find natives in roughly the same stage of culture."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "That is more to the interest of Lelianr."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel turned to his other daughter. "Time fleets like a meteor streak; I cannot believe that you have finished your first curricula. And now?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr spoke in the Sedate Counsel characterization. "I think in several directions. Primitive anthropology concerns me, and also food research. Last month I designed a very pleasant sugar, of which several tons were produced and distributed."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel laughed. "If you would discover new and exotic flavors, taste some of the Earther food."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr screwed her face into a wry grimace. "Animal tissues."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "They also consume much plant matter."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Life devouring life, nevertheless."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "An intrinsic immorality which I believe goes unrecognized. However, the race can synthesize only the simplest carbohydrates."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I suppose they must feed themselves somehow."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The Earthers are not entirely savage; indeed, if you decide to pursue your interest in proto-culture you will come upon some surprising achievements."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr shrugged. "There is still time before I need limit myself to rigid specialization."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Sia Spedz cried, "Look, two Earthers on the terrace!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel changed his characterization. "They are my servants\emdash both bright young men."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "They are not quite as I had pictured Earthers," Komeitk Lelianr remarked thoughtfully.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tcher said, "The darker of the two seems more agreeable; the other has weight on his soul."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "As a matter of fact," said Markel, "Roy has little liking for the Lekthwans."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tcher shook her head. "If the Klau had come to Earth in our place, then he would have grounds for resentment."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "He has grounds, of a rather personal nature. His father was a scientist, and Roy's ambition was to follow in his father's footsteps. From earliest youth he trained himself in the accepted techniques. Then the Lekthwans came, and overnight the entire effort of his life became nothing. Much of what he had learned was inaccurate, and the remainder, in the light of Lekthwan knowledge, was either obsolete or rudimentary. Roy became very bitter."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr studied Barch's back. "Understandably."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Why does he not study on Lekthwa?" demanded Sia Spedz.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel considered Barch and Darran. "He may approach the idea. At the moment all he sees is long years of further study, where he must start learning with children the age of Spedz."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The other," said Tcher, "indeed has a much kinder expression. What is his name?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That is Claude. He is more practical than Roy, and on the whole, less emotional. I plan to include him in the next group to Lekthwa."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And Roy?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "So far he has shown no inclination to leave Earth."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel's two guests entered the salon. He rose to his feet. "You have refreshed yourselves?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We have bathed and rested. The view from your dome is magnificent."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel nodded. "I consider Earth among (he more beautiful worlds. Have you noticed the valley to the southeast, the hundred soft colors?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Beautiful."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Beautiful, and also deadly. Indeed, the Earthers call it 'Death Valley.'"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\qj\f0\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\fs18 CHAPTER II \f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\par
\b\scaps\f0\fs18 Barch \b0\scaps0 and Darran cooked for themselves, with supplies delivered every Saturday by helicopter. By and large their duties were nominal, and after washing down the terrace, their mornings were free. During this time Darran studied the Lekthwan grammar texts and tape recordings that Markel had placed at his disposal, while Barch read or moodily \fs8 sunned\fs18  himself.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 The arrival of Markel's family disturbed the routine. On the morning after her arrival, Sia Spedz made friends with Darran, asking him why he wore shoes, rather than air-sandals.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Darran's answer was completely honest. "In the first place, I own no air-sandals. In the second, I'd fall flat on my face if I tried them."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "But it's not hard," said Sia Spedz, speaking English with a precise accent, "so long as you stay close to the ground."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't understand. Why should it be easier close to the ground?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The force comes out like a pyramid. Close to the ground the base is broad. The higher you walk, the narrower becomes the column you walk on, so much the harder to balance."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Ah," said Darran. "Why don't you make more powerful sandals, so that even when you walk high there would be a wide pyramid under your feet?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't know. I think because then there would be no fun in learning."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I thought you were a practical race," said Darran.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Not entirely. The Klau are completely practical. Everything is planned for exact use, whether it makes people happy or not. There is no gaiety on the Klau worlds."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "So? Who are the Klau?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\qj\f0\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\fs18 "Enemies. Terrible men, with eyes like red stars." But Sia Spedz was more interested in showing off her skill with the sandals. "Watch." She climbed into the air as if she were mounting stairs, ran gaily back and forth over Darran's head. "Now I'm going higher."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Be careful!" Darran walked back and forth below her with arms outstretched.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "This is as high as I like to go," said Sia Spedz. "Up here it's very shaky."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You'd better come down. You make me nervous."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She rejoined him. "Why don't you ask Markel to give you a pair of sandals?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran shrugged. "It's not polite to ask for gifts."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "If you don't make your wants known, they go unrecognized."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran laughed. "I thought you weren't a practical race."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Perhaps we are after all. In any event I'll give you a pair of sandals myself."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You'll get spanked for giving away your father's best shoes."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Sia Spedz giggled. "That's a funny thing to say."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch had been leaning on the balustrade. "I think he's funny too. He knows all kinds of games. Get him to teach you hopscotch."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Hopscotch?" Sia Spedz looked at Darran. "What's that?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's a game little Earth girls play."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Do you know how to play?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran scratched his cheek. "Roy plays a lot better than I do."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "No," said Barch," you won yesterday."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "You show me, Claude."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Barch sat down on a bench. "I'll see that there's no cheating." He reached under him, pulled out Darran's Lekthwan Primer. He flipped it open, and glanced at the introduction.\f1\fs24\par
\i\f0\fs18 The Lekthwan language, \i0 he read, \i sounds harsh and consonantal to Earth ears\emdash a matter which deserves explanation. To begin with, the Lekthwan language embraces a tremendous vocabulary, with sometimes a hundred synonyms for one basic idea. In consequence there is no need for circumlocution, and Lekthwan speech is notable for the logical simplicity of its declarative forms.\i0\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi202\sl-211\slmult0\qj\i\f0\fs18 A further peculiarity of the Lekthwan language is the fact that each word may have a number of different shadings, depending upon the "characterization" assumed by the person speaking, or even the person spoken to. There are almost a hundred of these characterizations, of which sixty-two are term "basic." Every mature person is familiar with the basic characterizations, and with most of the remaining optionals. The Lekthwan indicates the characterization in which he speaks by play of eyes, eyebrows and eyelashes. In crude analogy, the characterizations might be likened to the emotion-masks of the ancient Greek dramatists.\i0\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Barch tossed the book back to the bench, mentally labeling the Lekthwan language a life-time job in itself. The Lekthwan children seemed to absorb it easily enough. He watched Sia Spedz, engrossed in Darran's explanation. How many of these characterizations was she able to use? A bright-looking kid. Thousands of years of natural\emdash and possibly eugenic\emdash selection had no doubt increased the intelligence of the race. Intelligence and\emdash as if to offer an illustration, Komeitk Lelianr stepped out on the terrace\emdash intelligence and beauty.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Covertly he watched her as she leaned upon the balustrade. The Lekthwans, he knew, felt no self-consciousness in connection with nudity. Komeitk Lelianr now wore only a short skirt and air-sandals. Barch felt the warmth rising in his body. A stranger, a creature of a far world ... and yet how wonderful, how alive, how graceful, how clean....\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She turned quickly, as if she had felt his eyes. Barch looked away guiltily, then after a moment glanced back, to where she now stood with her back to the balustrade. She was appraising him. Barch thought bitterly, \i I'm the first Earther savage she's had a close look at.\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She said politely, "I see that you study our language. Do you find it difficult?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said, "At first glance it looks complicated. I imagine that it's a remarkable vehicle of expression, if a stranger could ever digest it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Her face showed interest. Barch thought angrily, she probably expected me to grunt like a bear.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr inquired, "Aren't you the one who doesn't like us?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch's eyes narrowed in surprise. He said carefully, "I don't object to Lekthwans as human beings."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And that's all you feel?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't think that Earth will ultimately benefit from their presence."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr asked, "What's your name?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Roy Barch." And almost rudely, he asked, "What's yours?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Komeitk Lelianr."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Mmph ... What does it mean?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She laughed. "A meaning? Why should it have a meaning?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It seems reasonable that an advanced people\emdash as you profess yourselves to be\emdash would use your names to indicate your profession, or home, or some kind of identification."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tsk," said Komeitk Lelianr. Her eyebrows moved in what Barch recognized as a change of characterization. "What a terrible idea: regimented, uniform. You suffer misapprehensions about us."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No less than your misapprehensions about us," growled Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr grinned. "Does your name mean anything?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "I'd like to ask a favor of you," she said. "You don't need to ask favors. I'm on the payroll; all you need to do is give orders."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'm very much interested in the psychology of other-world races. Would you object if I made a psychometric test of you?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Ah," said Barch bitterly. "So now it comes out. I'm to figure as one of your case histories ... Typical Earther savage. Perhaps you'd like a photograph of me in my- war-bonnet? Or maybe a recording of me in my native chants?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That would be wonderful," said Komeitk Lelianr. "But \emdash do you have your regalia here?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch stared at her. She was unquestionably serious. "We're going to throw a combination cannibal-feed and voodoo orgy tomorrow night on Sunset Boulevard. If you sneak quietly over in your air-sandals, you'll get some really sensational stuff."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Her eyebrows flickered in interest. "Indeed, I would like to visit one of these rites."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Well," said Barch thoughtfully, "you'd have to disguise yourself. If you powdered over your skin, you probably could pass for a good case of sun-tan. Also, you'd have to wear more clothes. That's a provocative outfit you've got on now."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'm not sure I understand. Why do you say that?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked away. "I don't know ... Yes, I do too."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Then how should I dress myself?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He looked sidewise at her. "Are you serious?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Of course. Where is this Sunset Boulevard?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I could take you," said Barch thoughtfully.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That would be very helpful."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch calculated. "How will we get there?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "In the air-boat. How else?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Your father won't kick?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Kick?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Object?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Of course not." She added soberly, "You must understand, I possibly intend to make anthropology my career." Barch nodded. "Very well, that's a date."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "But what sort of costume must I wear?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Anything that covers you from shoulder to knee. If you combed your hair back I suppose you could pass for platinum blonde..."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran came in while Barch was knotting his tie. "Where do you think you're going? Why the preparations?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Got a date with the old man's daughter."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran sat down. "So? Hopscotch with Spedz maybe, along the north terrace?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, sir. Catch-as-catch-can with the cute one, up to San Francisco."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran leaned back limply. "This is fantastic."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Not when you get the background. She's interested in picturesque native customs; she thinks she's going to Los Angeles to see a human sacrifice, or a Dionysian fertility rite."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Darran sighed. "What some guys won't do to get a date ... And where are you taking her? Or is she taking you?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Darned if I know. She'd probably enjoy the Embarcadero saloons or Chutes at the Beach." He made a wry face. "I have my pride too."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "She'd be bored at the Fairmont."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "I should think so. No blood-letting, no colorful rituals."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "There's always Hambone Kelly's."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "True," said Barch. "There's always Hambone Kelly's." He buttoned his jacket. "Well, here I go."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Good luck," said Darran. "Don't get in any trouble."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch turned him a cool stare. "What do you mean by that?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Nothing," said Darran mildly. "You're a truculent son-of-a-gun. You must have something on your mind."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch pushed out upon the terrace and stood looking into the night. His hands were clammy and tense; Darran had hit close to the truth. This was like going out on the first date of his life, only more so.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He walked slowly around the terrace, stopped near the main dome. Inside were Lekthwans, from a far planet; did they expect him to knock on the door, call for the girl? Or should he wait outside until she appeared? He made an angry sound through his teeth; where was his self-respect? He was as good as any of them; this was Earth, by God, they'd go by Earth customs.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He strode belligerently up to the dome, then came to a halt. Knock, certainly. Or ring a bell. But where?\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Light glimmered through the opacity; Barch backed away. Komeitk Lelianr came quickly out upon the terrace, followed by Markel and Sia Spedz running like a terrier.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Markel spoke in Lekthwan. "I imagine you'll be disappointed. Of course there's no reason why you shouldn't investigate."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Sia Spedz said, "I'd like to go too."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "One anthropologist in the family is enough," said Markel. He turned to Barch. "See that she does nothing to get into trouble, Roy."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tsk." Komeitk Lelianr sauntered down the terrace. "Come, Roy."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch, mustered his dignity, followed to where the air-boat floated.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr ducked into the air-boat, Barch followed She wore a white and black one-piece suit, like a harlequin costume. She would be conspicuous, but would not necessarily draw a crowd.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Inside the boat floated a silver ball pierced by a black rod. Komeitk Lelianr took the ball; the car moved off into the sky. "Now," said she, "which way?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The first thing, thought Barch, was to get the affair on its proper footing. "Show me how to run this contraption."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She turned her head, her eyebrows raised in surprise. For a moment Barch thought she might politely ignore him; then she handed him the silver ball. "This"\emdash  she touched the black rod\emdash "represents the perpendicular axis of the boat. Tilt the ball, the boat tilts. Move the ball up, you initiate a cumulative upward acceleration, which can only be countered by moving the ball down. The black rod is the speed control. The farther you depress it, the faster you go. To brake, you push from below."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That's simple enough. Where's the height indicator?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "There. She pointed to a series of angular black shapes moving along a pale gray band. "This is both the altimeter and the speed indicator. The green circle in the middle represents the boat. The outline of the shadow depicts the profile of the land directly ahead. The lower you fly, the larger becomes the green circle. The green touches the black when the boat touches ground."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch nodded. "It seems easy enough."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She watched intently for a moment or two, then asked, "Where are you heading?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We're going to a place called Hambone Kelly's across the bay from San Francisco. Or would you prefer a more decorous approach to Earth night-life?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I suppose I must rely upon your judgment as to what might interest me."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't know much about your frame of mind. Tell me something, how old are you?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Fifty-two." At Barch's surprised glance, she explained. "That would be twenty of your years."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Your name is hard to pronounce," said Barch. "I'll call you 'Ellen.'"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 In the dark he could not see the expression of her face. "Whatever is convenient for you."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Hills brought angular shapes to the altimeter band.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A long carpet of light spread out below: San Leandro, Oakland, Berkeley. Barch flew a thousand feet over the shore of the bay, slanted down over San Pablo Avenue. "I think there's a vacant lot where we can leave the boat. Yes, there."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He set the car down behind a row of eucalyptus trees. "Now we start."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 From Hambone Kelly's, music came loud and strong to the street.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Interesting music. The people do interpretative dancing, I suppose, with sexual symbolism," said Komeitk Lelianr.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Well, I don't know about that. It's energetic dancing, at least. But I really brought you to hear the music\emdash a special kind of music that may be new to you."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She listened. "Eight-part polyphony, is it not?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch started at her. "There's only seven pieces in the band."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "There's one\emdash a tinkling kind of harp that's playing in two parts."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Oh, the piano." Barch suddenly felt glum. "Let's go in."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He led her to a dim table. On a raised stage stood seven men playing trumpet, trombone, clarinet, piano, drums, banjo, and brass bass. They played with brilliant emphasis; music poured forth clear and impelling.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said close to Komeitk Lelianr's ear, "This is the Yerba Buena Jazz Band. They're playing a tune called \i Weary Blues."\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It sounds not at all weary."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, quite the reverse." Barch turned to watch the band.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Music came in a tide, the trumpet ringing like a bar of pure energy; the trombone dark, rough, hoarse; the clarinet a fiery bird. There came the final chatter and smash of traps, then the sigh of release from the audience, deep from the stomach, the chest, the throat.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch turned to Komeitk Lelianr. "What do you think of it?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It seems loud and emotional."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's the music of our times," said Barch fervently. "It reflects our racial drive; it's the best of our contemporary creativeness."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr leaned forward. "You appear to think in symbolic images," she remarked. "Am I right?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't know," replied Barch impatiently. "It's not important; won't you forget primitive anthropology for awhile?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch saw her eyebrows flicker. "You do it automatically," he said bitterly.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "What?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Jump into characterizations. Find whatever role works out best at the moment, then get into it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She frowned. "I've never thought of it in quite that way."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He made an impatient gesture. "Forget it. Listen to the music. That's why I brought you here."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr listened. "Very interesting. But it jars me. It's too forthright, too uncompromising."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, no," cried Barch, with no very clear idea of what proposition he was contradicting. He spoke on with great intensity, wanting to arouse in her a feeling for the music and, by extension, himself. "By your time-scale, we're a young people. Your own world is quiet, your people are settled, complacent. Earth is different! This is an exciting time for Earth\emdash the more so since the coming of the Lekthwans. Every day is new, fresh; every day sees something started, progress made toward a goal. We live with this drive, this thrust to the future\emdash a dynamism that speaks in music."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He waited but Komeitk Lelianr said nothing. Her thoughts were unreadable.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch qualified. "I should say, the spirit of our section of the world. On other continents people live differently, and their music is different. The Chinese consider all our music marching music\emdash jazz, chamber music, hymns, dirges, all of it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A waitress approached. "Order, please?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tom Collins, a pair," said Barch. He said to Komeitk Lelianr, "But we are the dominant force, the leaders\emdash or were, until the Lekthwans came."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She laughed. "You forgot that for a few moments."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yes. So I did."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Why do you tell me all this?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch hesitated, then took the plunge. "Because I don't consider myself a barbarian. I'm your equal, whether you like it or not. And\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The waitress placed a pair of tall glasses in front of them. "Dollar twenty, please."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch dropped money on the tray.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr touched the glass, smelled it gingerly, "What is this?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Fruit juice, carbonated water, ethyl alcohol, sugar."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Living matter?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "What if it is?" snapped Barch. "Basically, it's carbon, oxygen, hydrogen; what difference does it make where it came from? The fruit is dead now."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 She screwed up her face, sipped. "It's not unpleasant. Are these glasses sterile?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Probably not. That's why they put the alcohol in\emdash to sterilize the glasses."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Oh."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 They sat in silence. The band returned to the stand and Barch felt Komeitk Lelianr's dispassionate observation of the music, then an equally dispassionate study of the dancers.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He set his shoulders, leaned forward. "I'm sorry I brought you out under false pretenses."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She said wistfully, "Then there really are none of the ceremonies you described?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Perhaps in the middle of Africa."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "One of the remoter districts?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yes, quite remote," said Barch sardonically. "A different race of people entirely, as different from us as\emdash " He was about to add, \i as we are from you, \i0 then stopped short. He drank from the tall green glass.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He pointed to a Negro sitting at a table nearby. "That man is of African stock."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Oh? He seems no different from you except in skin coloring. Does he practice the ceremonies you speak of?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, of course not. He's been born into our society. He does however, sometimes run into unpleasant discrimination." And he added maliciously, "Much, I suspect, as Earthers on Lekthwa experience."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr pursed her lips, turned the tall glass between her fingers. Barch noticed that she had barely tasted the drink. "Don't you like it?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She looked down indifferently, sipped at the straws. "Should I now feel exhilarated?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Not unless you drink two or three more."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She shook her head. "That's not likely." She rose to her feet. "Now we will go."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Sullenly Barch followed her out to the street, and back to the air-boat. Fighting to keep control of his voice he said, "If you are interested in sordid spectacles, I could take you to a prize fight or a wrestling match\emdash although I'd prefer not."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 She looked at him reflectively. "It would embarrass you?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Yes. It would embarrass me."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 She shrugged. "Then we will return to the dome." She stepped through the hull, into the air-boat.\f1\fs24\par
