\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 CHAPTER III \f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\par
\b\scaps\f0\fs18 The \b0\scaps0 boat rose into the night, automatically turned back toward Markel's dome, far to the south. San Pablo Avenue became a bright artery, flowing with twinkling headlight corpuscles. Overhead, the sky was luminous, dusted with the glow from a million lights.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 The boat flew south across the great central valley. The cities became blurs of lights astern; the sky was dark and bright with stars.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said softly, "I can see my native sun, up by that bright star...."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That's Spica."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Up and to the left is a fainter star\emdash Skyl, our sun."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch contemplated the star without interest. "You sound as if you're homesick."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She nodded. "It's very lonely on a strange planet with none of my friends; therefore I seek to bury myself in study."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch lapsed into moody silence.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Suddenly, low ahead, an intense green flash appeared in the sky. Komietk Lelianr jerked up in her seat. A frightened sound came from her throat.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch sat up. "What's the matter?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't know...." She drove home the speed button.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Shadows fled across the altimeter band. Komeitk Lelianr sat tense, clutching her knees; Barch looked uneasily ahead. Snowy peaks gleamed below; a few moments later Markel's dome appeared, faintly luminescent, peaceful.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The air-boat slowed, dropped, settled into its bay.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr stepped quickly out. Barch followed. On the terrace she froze into a statue. Barch asked anxiously, "What's the trouble?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't know. I feel something\emdash bad."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch started around the dark terrace. Fibers of green light glowed in the blue glass under his feet.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Ahead lay something dark. Barch ran forward, the muscles of his throat tight and stiff. He knelt slowly. Claude Darran. Barch stared in astonishment. Cold, dead\emdash unthinkable!\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A shape stood behind him: Komeitk Lelianr. Barch rose numbly to his feet. He walked forward; two paces, four\emdash  another dark shape. It was small, sprawled carelessly. Behind him he heard horrified gasping sounds. Barch's neck was cold as ice. He bent beside the pitiful object that had been Sia Spedz; then, rising quickly, drew Komeitk Lelianr to the balustrade.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She said in an agonized whisper, "The Klau\emdash they have come to Earth. They have been here..."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch peered into the darkness, feeling ineffectual, indecisive. He had no real desire to investigate, to confront a set of other-world murderers. From the inside of the dome came a sudden thud. Komeitk Lelianr whimpered, jerked forward.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Spasmodic strength came to Barch's legs; he shoved ahead of her, moved toward the dim-glowing portal. Cautiously he looked within: nothing but an article or two of furniture. Komeitk Lelianr pressed against his back, breathing in soft sobs. He ducked inside; Komeitk Lelianr ran ahead, thrust aside a curtain of green smoke. She froze, arms and legs at grotesque angles.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked over her shoulder, down at two golden bodies.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was a great deal of blood, puddled and netted along the floor. Barch drew the dazed girl back.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She said, "I must communicate...." She walked awkwardly across the room, waved open a portal. Two more corpses\emdash Markel's guests. And at the communication table sat a great black creature. Stiff black bristles framed his face; his eyes gleamed tike polished jet, with red four-pronged centers.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Klau stared at Barch; Barch's legs were numb, wooden. Grumbling, mumbling, the Klau rose, clutching a heavy black dagger.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch backed sweating against the wall; the Klau hacked. Barch caught the black wrist, planted a foot in the belly, kicked. The Klau lurched, toppled, fell with a dull roar of rage.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch, grinning like a wolf, planted his foot in the pulpy neck. Thick hands seized his ankle; Barch swayed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He heard a hiss, a grunt. The hands clenched, the four-pronged red stars widened, slowly folded in on themselves.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr arose from the dagger in the black chest.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Come, we must go," she panted. "There are others!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She ran to the portal. Barch paused to wrench at the dagger. He heard a thin scream, looked up, saw a flurrying black shape. Something heavy, furry, enveloped him. His legs were swept out from under him and he was carried off like a swaddled child.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Hands gripped him hard, heaved. He was free, falling, falling\emdash a hundred feet, a thousand feet, mile after mile....\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kicking frantically, Barch freed himself from the fur robe. Still falling ... Strange there was no rush of wind, no pound or flutter at his arms and legs. He stiffened to rigidity. The air was calm. He was suspended, floating in darkness; lack of gravity gave the illusion of free fall. Now his eyes adapted themselves, he could see walls glowing with a dull maroon light, as if red-hot. But the air was cold, there was no heat on his face.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr floated quietly over his head. He caught an ankle, drew her down. Her eyes were closed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch relaxed like a spent swimmer. Events were moving too fast. He wondered, am I awake or asleep? This is too fantastic for reality. He tried to rouse himself, without success. I am already awake, he decided.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Inspecting the surroundings, he saw that they floated in an ovular cell with no apparent entrance. He felt, as much as heard, a high-pitched whine, so shrill as to be nearly inaudible.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch closed his eyes. He wanted to sleep, forget, ignore.... He felt a stirring beside him. Komeitk Lelianr opened her eyes. She was completely matter-of-fact. She felt her head, licked her lips, looked around. Her eyes rested dispassionately on Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch steadied his voice. "Well?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We're in a Klau ship."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Where are they taking us? Why haven't they killed us?" Komeitk Lelianr shrugged. "Corpses are valueless. We probably will end up at Magarak."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Magarak?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "A manufacturing center."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "But-"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We're slaves."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Oh." Before Barch's eyes flashed scenes of Earth, like color slides. All this he was leaving. All this he would see no more. In a strained voice he said, "And what is this Magarak like?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Gray. Dank. Cold."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch felt a spasm of rage\emdash toward Komeitk Lelianr, toward the Lekthwans. Why should he suffer in their quarrel? "Why don't the Lekthwans do something about these Klau?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr smiled half-contemptuously. "There are three Lekthwan planets, forty-two Klau worlds. There is war between us that perhaps you cannot completely understand \emdash a long-range combat of our moral vitality. In the end we will win. Meanwhile many people suffer." She shrugged. "The universe is not a paradise."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No," said Barch. Earth suddenly seemed very small and negligible, a bucolic backwater off to one side of the space-empires. "So then\emdash we spend the rest of our lives on Magarak?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She made no answer. Barch glanced desperately around the glowing walls. "Can't we be ransomed, can't we escape?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She spoke slowly, as if to a child. "Ransom is inapplicable; there is no medium of exchange between Lekthwa and the Klau. The Klau have energy, raw material, technical skill. Labor is the scarcest commodity of the universe; labor is the Klau wealth."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "And escape?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She shrugged. "Recently a dozen Lenape hid in a false cargo blister, and reached the Maha Triad. If they find a way home to Lenau, the Klau will suffer. If they are recaptured \emdash the Klau will use them to discourage others."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The main difficulty seems to be in leaving the planet."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Exactly."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Time passed, perhaps two days. Three times the walls swelled into blisters, bursting with a pop to eject packets of gray mush into the cell.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr had completely withdrawn into herself. She spoke no words to Barch, ignored the food. Finally Barch pushed himself across to her. "If you don't eat, you'll be weak. You'll get sick."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She looked at him languidly. "What then?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch truculently knit his brows. "What's the trouble? Given up?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "What is there to give up?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Confidence."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She said in a soft voice, "We're slaves; slaves have no need for confidence."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'm not a slave until I feel like a slave."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Something seemed to give way inside of her. Her voice became harsh. "You have no concept of Magarak's reality; you refuse to think; you live by ready-made emotional doctrines\emdash a substitute for thought. What is worse, you try to wrench reality to fit your ideas."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I've heard all that before," said Barch evenly. "Sometimes the emotional doctrines work out. Do you know why?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Why?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Because neither you nor I are really pals with reality. We don't know whose emotional doctrine fits. Anyway, whether it's impossible or not, if there's a way out of this Magarak slave camp I'll try to find it\emdash and I'll take you with me if I can.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She said wearily, "Your ideas are not well-formed. You can't escape Magarak merely because you have the will to escape."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch laughed grimly. "I certainly can't escape without it. Those twelve Lenape got loose."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "There's a great difference; they are a highly developed race; they have a feeling for the organization of Magarak.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Also, they were in a position to control the growth of the ship on which they escaped."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-250\slmult0\qc\f0\fs18 "Growth?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Yes, certainly. Ships are grown, like you Earthers grow cabbages. The Lenapes are experts in the techniques of growth matter; on Lenau they grow their dwellings, their ocean-ships their air-ships. On Lekthwa much the same is true."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch grinned. "That's a point of difference between us. We grow our food and build our space-ships. You grow your ships and build your food."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said listlessly, "It's easier to grow ships than to build them. When you become proficient in spaceship design you will recognize the advantages."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Well, cabbages, space-ships, Lenape aside, there are other ways of escape."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "How?" She laughed shortly. "You know nothing of Magarak. You cannot imagine it. It's not a matter of killing a guard, jumping a fence and running."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I didn't say I'd succeed. I said I'd \i try."\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She smiled. "Yes. The dynamic thrust of your race."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked at her with near-dislike. "Call it anything you want. Maybe when a race gets old like yours, it gets stale, sour."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Perhaps." She stretched out her legs, her arms. After a moment she turned her head, looked at him with what seemed new curiosity. "Your optimism is stimulating, in any event."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch grinned. Ages ago, Claude Darran had spoken of Barch's capacity for optimism in different terms.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 As if following his thoughts, Komeitk Lelianr murmured, "What strange life-lines we weave through the cosmic gel. Three days ago..."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 For the first time, Barch saw tears in her eyes.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Time passed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Without warning, the cell burst open. White light dazzled their eyes; there was a wave of sound, a tumble of black shapes. The white light cut off, the walls were whole. The cell suddenly seemed full of ill-smelling flesh.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch pressed back against the wall. There were eight newcomers, six men, two women: squat white creatures with moist bulldog faces. They wore thread-bare gray smocks, leather stockings, shoes like blobs of yellow gum.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said tonelessly, "Modoks. I thought it strange the hold was given to us alone."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Warily Barch watched the sight. Their faces showed no emotion, no expression. There was a hoarse conversation, then dead silence while all of them inspected Barch and Komeitk Lelianr.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said with a tinge of interest in her voice, "I would fit them approximately at 14-90, by the Epignotic Cultural Calculation. Notice the cloth of their garments; durable, shaped rather than woven; their shoes, molded permanently to their feet. These must be outdoor serfs, in the service of a Technics Lord."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch made a non-committal sound.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Not an uncommon pattern around the universe," she went on in a monotone. "Their lot will change little for better or worse."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch muttered, "I wonder how much longer we'll be in this hold."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Are you anxious for Magarak?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, but I don't like the smell here."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You might sometime wish yourself back in this cell."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Do you think they'll separate us?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Certainly," she said in a flat voice. "First the slaves are graded at rough intellectual levels; they must pass through a hall filled with traps, pitfalls, obstacles, unpleasant sensations, and the like, which they avoid according to their intelligence. After this first division, the lower grades are classified by physique, agility, dexterity." She looked across the cell. "These serfs will probably go out to the mud-flats along Xolboar Sea, a great reclamation project, which uses up thousands of labor-units a year."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And how about us?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "A thousand possibilities."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch awoke to a sound of harsh voices. He crouched instinctively, slowly relaxed. Two of the blank-faced serfs were fighting, clawing clumsily at each other's faces. The remaining men and the women watched critically.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Disgusting animals," said Komeitk Lelianr.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 One of the contestants suddenly ceased to fight. The other put his legs against the square back, jerked back at the head. The eyes stared up, the neck snapped. There came a sudden raucous babble.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "What are they fighting about?" Barch asked in bewilderment.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Impossible to say."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Look!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The two women were slapping at the man who had conquered, stolidly without anger. At last he threw up his hands as if in defeat, crossed to a man who had been watching, caught him by the neck, smashed his head against the wall until the skull became like jelly. The women spoke on angrily for a few moments, then appeared to lose interest. No one heeded the limp bodies. There were a few dark glances cast toward Barch and Komeitk Lelianr, one or two monosyllables, then silence.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said speculatively, "I wonder what would happen..." He looked thoughtfully at Komeitk Lelianr. "Off hand, would you say that these creatures will be well-treated on Magarak?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She examined him curiously. "I have no idea. We know very little of Magarak. I assume that they are not as strictly supervised as the technical workers."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Suppose the Klau found a body in your clothes and a body in mine..."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr shuddered. "You want me to wear those clothes?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We have nothing to lose, perhaps something to gain."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She shook her head. "But I see no reason\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "If we get sent out to those mud-flats, we go out together!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Oh," said Komeitk Lelianr in sudden enlightenment. "The dynamic attitude, this tinkering with destiny...."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yes," said Barch grimly. "If I couldn't be doing something, I might as well throw in the sponge. Are you game?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She shrugged. "It makes no difference."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch flushed. "If you'd rather go it alone, say so."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, Roy. I don't object to you personally."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Thanks," growled Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She smiled. "Maybe our friends won't like us undressing their dead."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We'll soon see..."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He pushed himself over to the nearest body, and with a challenging survey of the six white faces, began to jerk the gray garment loose.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was an undertone of muttering. Black eyes became beady and thoughtful. No one stirred. Underneath the jacket was a skin-tight coverall of matted fiber. "This is the smallest," said Barch. "Let's have your clothes."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr slipped out of the white and black harlequin costume, climbed gingerly into the black smock.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch stripped the second corpse down to the gray matted undersuit, pulled off his coat and trousers. Closing his nostrils to the sour odor of the garment, he pulled it over his head.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was motion along the wall. Barch looked up sharply. One of the men was feeling the material of his coat. \i My good gray flannel, \i0 thought Barch. He jerked it away, started to pull it on the corpse.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Now there were mutters. The older of the women made a furious babbling sound; the other made a gesture with stiff fingers against her lips. Barch ignored the noise, buttoned the coat, began to pull the legs into the trousers. The legs were too short; the cuffs dragged ridiculously over the yellow blobs of wax or resin that covered the dead man's feet.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 From the corner of his eye Barch saw Komeitk Lelianr deftly thrusting the second body into her black and white costume. He turned, critically inspected her gleaming silver hair. "You don't make a very good peasant."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He looked around the cell. One of the Modoks wore a loose conical cap. Barch pushed himself forward, reached out, took the cap. The man half-heartedly clutched for the cap, then backed away, eyes staring with frantic alarm.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The women babbled in approval.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch yanked the cap down on Komeitk Lelianr's hair. "There," he said, inspecting her, "that's a little better." He turned to look at their cellmates. "They're certainly an odd-acting bunch."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's all relative," said Komeitk Lelianr. "They undoubtedly think the same of us."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked down at his shoes, at Komeitk Lelianr's sandals. "Do you think we'll pass?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I couldn't say."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The ship shivered; they heard deep clanking sounds, like an anchor-chain running down a hawse-pipe. "What's that?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't know. Perhaps we have arrived."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "If so, we didn't get changed any too soon."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The ship jarred; the red glow in the wall pulsed bright and dim. A moment later the cell burst open. Gravity seized at the ten bodies\emdash eight living, two dead. They slid down the cell wall, together with all the accumulated litter, trash and refuse, down to a smooth chute. Fresh air was cold on their faces; sound roared at their ears.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch's eyes smarted under the sudden light, his legs felt limp at the knees. "Ellen!" he cried. "Ellen, where are you?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Blinking, he looked around him. They stood in a fenced enclosure, like a cattle pen. Komeitk Lelianr was a few feet distant, holding to her cap, which the original owner was attempting to reclaim. Barch staggered over, struck the man with his fist.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Something stung at his back, burning like fire; he turned, snarling. Above him, on a ramp, stood a tremendous man with blood-red skin. Black spikes of hair extended like quills on all sides of his head. He had eyes with red four-starred centers, like the Klau, and he carried a tube with a flickering serpent of light darting up, down, in, out.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He roared at Barch in a voice like a brass horn, flourished the flail. A disturbance in the adjoining pen attracted his attention. He pounded down the ramp. The flickering light-snake curled out. Barch heard a sharp cry.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He gained Komeitk Lelianr's side, dazed and angry, shook his head as if to clear it of confusion, glowered up at the trumpeting red whip-wielders.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Directly overhead a hatch opened; a stream of bodies plummeted at him. He jumped aside, pushed Komeitk Lelianr against the fence, away from the milling center of the pen, and here he caught his breath.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The ship continued to discharge. Men and women tumbled, slid, spewed from orifices under the ship, their fall broken by the bawling bodies below.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Past the great hulk, Barch glimpsed the shapes of the two other ships. Beyond rose the facade of a building a mile high, the roof-line blurred in fog. There was a steady roar in the air, like the sound of surf; a smell of mud, rust and ammonia hung across the pens.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said coolly in his ear, "We're part of a not-too-valuable cargo. We'll be worked very hard; we'll die very quickly."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He looked at her truculently. "You sound as if you don't care."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I know what to expect. This is Magarak."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said, "Personally, I'm scared stiff."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She shrugged. "Adjust yourself; your fear will pass."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch glared. "Adjust myself be damned! I'm almost afraid that I won't be able to make these devils regret the day they saw me!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She glanced up to the top of the ramp. "The Podruods will soon curse you of that."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "They have eyes like the Klau."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "They're a sub-species of Klau. There are Big Klau, Little Klau, Bornghaleze, Podruods\emdash all Klau stock. The Podruods are the troops, the guards, the fighters."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A metallic clatter rang out, accompanied by distant shouts. Barch, turning his head, saw a long feather-shaped boom vibrating back and forth across the sky. Overhead six white balls snapped past\emdash one after the other, like rockets.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He said in Komeitk Lelianr's ears, "This is bedlam."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She nodded briefly. "Compared to other parts of Magarak it's quiet."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Podruod voice rang out above like a clarion. "Hey! Hey! Hey!" Directly behind them the fence opened. "I guess we move," muttered Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A sudden rush of gray bodies with frightened white faces surged past. Knobby shoulders pummeled Barch. "Ellen!" he cried. He looked all around desperately. "Ellen! Where are you? Ellen!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Arms thrust angrily at him, he was carried along the tide. "Ellen!" He thought he heard his name; he stopped to listen. Nothing but the shuffle and thud of feet, ringing shouts of the great red Podruods.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A chute loomed ahead. Four abreast the Modoks scuttled up, jumped down into what appeared to be a long black barge. A Podruod with legs painted blue stood in the stern, his face working like rubber, yelling, crying.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch craned his neck, searching the sea of alien faces. Fifty feet ahead he saw Komeitk Lelianr. "Ellen!" She turned her head. A great red hand obscured her face; she stumbled up the chute.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A second chute opened at Barch's right; the Podruods roared new directions.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch pushed forward, now shoving against the tide. He saw Komeitk Lelianr half-way up the chute. The Podruod roared, struck at him; the light-serpent snapped out.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch fell to his knees; feet pressed around him, stepping on his hands, his legs.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He crawled doggedly through, saw massive Podruod legs ahead. In sudden fury, he dove forward, tackled the legs. The great body toppled; the light-whip rolled in the dust. Barch snatched at it, missed. He rose to his feet, raced up the chute, pressed into the last of the group.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 From behind came a hoarse yelling; Barch, glancing over his shoulder, saw a clot of Modoks kicking at the great spiked head, smiling, laughing.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Podruods came pounding along the ramp; light-snakes darted; the gray men dutifully marched into the chutes. The red man writhed, kicked on the ground like a beetle on its back.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch pushed ahead. "Ellen!" He grasped her arm. "I thought I had lost you."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She took his hand, squeezed it tight. Barch's heart gave a sudden throb of joy. It was almost worth coming to Magarak.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A gate clanged behind them. The barge shuddered, rose into the air, slid clear of the slave yard.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch and Komeitk Lelianr, the last aboard, leaned against the rail. Komeitk Lelianr motioned toward the panorama. "Now, look at Magarak...."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\par
\fs18 CHAPTER IV \f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\par
\b\scaps\f0\fs18 The \b0\scaps0 scene was too vast, too complex for mental grasp. Barch sensed flaring lights, gigantic objects in motion, monstrous shapes. Near at hand the lights were like openings into furnaces: yellow, orange, greenish-white, red; at the horizon they gleamed and flickered like stars.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Heavy sound came at a constant grumbling pitch, so far-reaching that it seemed an intrinsic property of the planet. Across the sky moved endless shapes\emdash booms swinging in low circles, black objects like spiders darting along glistening tracks, barges floating at various levels, blast of dark vapor. Then underneath were the buildings: grayish-white, greenish-gray, black, orange, some faintly etched with window lines, others blank as new paper. Between were dark crevasses flickering with yellow or bluish glow far at the bottom.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch looked up into the sky, smoky, sooty, lumpy with low clouds. "Is it day or night? It must be day."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr asked wryly, "What do you think of Magarak?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I feel like an ant in a thrashing machine," said Barch. He looked around the horizon. "How far does the madhouse go on?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We must be on Kdoa," she mused. "A large continent\emdash  about five thousand of your miles wide."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Five thousand miles of this!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She nodded. "Underneath are the barracks, the commissaries, the nurseries."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Nurseries\emdash for what?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Slave children. Slaves are encouraged to breed. The women become pregnant often to avoid heavy work. The children make the best slaves; they know no other kind of life."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch silently watched the shapes and lights of Magarak drift past below.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Do you still think you can"\emdash she nodded\emdash "defeat this?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked at her resentfully. "Do you think I won't try?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No. I think you'll try. I think you'll end up on the grid." She added tonelessly, "That's where the slaves are punished."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch stared over the side. Another barge drifted toward them, passed two hundred feet below. Barch saw six long dark shapes, like spindles, caught the white flash of upturned faces. The barges drifted apart.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The sea spread leaden, listless; they drifted over dreary mud-flats. Ahead appeared a long black line which, as the barge drew near, broke up into clots of men, piles of cut stone, spidery cranes. A coffer dam of mud had been scraped up against the sea; in deep oozing pits, workers, moving slow as cold ants, fitted great stones together.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That's what you'll be doing," said Komeitk Lelianr in a flat voice.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch stared down into the dismal pits. "And what happens to the women?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Some other kind of work. Chipping stone, perhaps."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 They passed a barge loaded with granite blocks. Barch asked, "What keeps these barges up? Do they use the same machinery as the spaceships?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "I would imagine so." Her voice was disinterested. "The principle of plane-cohesion is fundamental."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "But they could leave the planet?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I suppose so." She watched the reclamation project fall astern. "We're not bound there, at least."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 The ocean shore curved away behind them; a range of mountains loomed dark ahead. The sky was darkening rapidly. The sun had settled beyond the overcast. "I wonder how much farther?" asked Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr knit her brows. "If those mountains are the Palamkum, then that was Tchul Sea, and this is Kredbon instead of Kdoa. I think Xolboar Sea is beyond those mountains."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Then we get sorted out and put to work?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "I suppose so."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Barch examined the mountains with interest. They were great masses of white rock, split by deep valleys and gorges. Black vegetation carpeted the valley slopes; snow gleamed on the high cols and peaks.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch said in a hushed voice, "Can your shoes hold up both of us?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She looked at him first in startled wonder, then speculatively. "No."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Suppose we jumped off the barge."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "If I could stay on my feet, we'd drop slowly."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We'd never be caught down there."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She stared down into the dark wilderness. "We'd starve to death."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Maybe, maybe not. At least we would be free. We'd be out of the mud-pits, out of the slave barracks."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She glanced at the Modoks, made up her mind. "Very well. Try to put your feet on top of mine."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked over the side. They flew over a long valley. "Now," muttered Barch. "Are you ready?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yes."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Now!" He jumped up, straddled the rail. Komeitk Lelianr climbed nimbly after. Startled white faces turned. There was an excited chatter, a couple of arms tentatively outstretched.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch bared his teeth, kicked. The commotion attracted the eye of the Podruod controller. With great lunging strides he came forward.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'm ready," panted Komeitk Lelianr. "Step on my feet."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch jumped down, clasped her around the waist; they toppled off into gray air. He glimpsed the rectangular hull of the barge slipping past overhead with a hundred little nubbins of heads silhouetted against the twilight. Sky and mountains whirled in sickening topsy-turvy motion.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr was crying in his ear. "My feet, my feet!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch clamped his legs around hers, set his feet on her instep. He felt a braking, the sky and mountains steadied.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Looking anxiously aloft he saw the raft drifting quietly on; the cargo was fuzzy gray, like a load of jute. He turned his eyes down. A massive crag, like a rotten tooth, stabbed up at them with frightening velocity; below was the vast slot of a valley, the shining trickle of a river.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We're braking," she said. "The lower we get, the slower we fall."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch relaxed, tried to follow her as she shifted weight. Dark fronds of vegetation reached up at them. Thirty feet ... twenty feet ... ten feet...\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was the crash, scatter, agitation of breaking stems and snapping branches. Barch saw the ground, the black humus of the hillside; at six feet he jumped, so as not to land with Komeitk Lelianr's feet under his. She cried out in surprise. Relieved of Barch's weight, she bounced back into the air. She caught at branches swung back and forth like an acrobat, then slowly settled, to the ground.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 They had landed on a high slope. The sky was a black ceiling overhead; dank wind blew roaring through the valley below. Trees flapped and clattered; from the far distance came a harsh gurgling whistle. Komeitk Lelianr whispered, "What's that?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said, "It's breakfast, if I can catch it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "In the dark it might catch you."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 They looked down the slope, found the river. "We'll be warmer up here," said Barch, "out of the valley. We'd better not build a fire until we learn more about the country."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 In a little hollow under a rock he piled moss, dry humus, and contrived a covering of fronds wrenched down from the trees. "Like sleeping in a haystack," said Barch. "You get in first."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Rain fell during the night, but the wind blew it over the rock, and they stayed dry. Magarak morning came damp and gray.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Ouch!" said Barch, "my aching bones." He felt his face. "At least, no whiskers. I've got your father to thank for that."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-250\slmult0\qc\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr sat brushing moss off her gray smock. Barch went on cheerfully. "Next\emdash breakfast. Are you hungry?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 She made no answer.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch rose to his feet, looked carefully up and down the hillside. The trees by daylight were like kelp: black and brown, with red veins along the leaves. Overhead the sky was heavy with clouds.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch pulled down a branch, broke free a cluster of nuts. He broke one of these open, smelled, recoiled from the acrid odor. "No nourishment here. Let's see what's down by the water."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Cautiously they made their way downhill to the river. Standing in a pool was a blackish-green creature with the head of an owl, a bat's wings, the legs of a heron. It watched them approach, then fluttered up, flapped croaking off down the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That's a good sign," said Barch. "It means that there's something to be caught. That bird wasn't just taking a bath."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We catch things\emdash then eat them?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We're savages now," said Barch airily. "Both of us, remember?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I remember very well."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch crept forward, crouched down by the edge of the pool. Water swirled quietly over round stones of various colors. He scanned the bottom. One of the round stones moved. Barch grabbed shoulder-deep into water like ice, came up with a squirming bulb. Dangling tentacles flapped, wound around his wrist; his skin burned as if singed with flame. Barch cursed, threw the bulb up on the shore. It scuttled toward the river. Barch kicked it back, dropped a chunk of rock on it. When he picked up the rock, there was nothing below but a mat of whitish fibers and ooze.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch turned away in disgust. A red weal had formed along his wrist, the bones of his forearm ached. "Let's go on downstream," he said through his teeth. "Maybe we'll find something a little less hard to get along with."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The river flowed smoothly a hundred yards, then began to drop. It pounded over step-like ledges, split itself against boulders. Scrambling over the wet rocks, Barch almost fell a dozen times. Glancing over his shoulder, he saw Komeitk Lelianr walking serenely two or three feet over the river.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Said Barch quizzically, "I wish I had a pair of sandals."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr made no reply.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "How long will the power hold out?" Barch asked.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "With steady use, perhaps a month or two."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And how high can you walk?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Two or three hundred feet. Higher, if I take care."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Suppose you walk up fifty feet, and tell me what you see."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Swaying and stepping as if walking on stilts, she rose into the air. The wind caught her, carried her drifting down the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch scrambled over the rocks to keep abreast. "What do you see?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Rocks, more black trees, a lake."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "No smoke? No buildings?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Nothing." She came back down in great sliding steps. "Do you dunk we'll find anything to eat?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Of course," Barch said confidently. "Down by the lake, perhaps."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A few minutes later the valley widened. Before them spread the lake, roughly circular, surrounded first by a rim of marsh, then a strip of open slope overgrown with thorny bush. Each bush terminated in a tight green sac, like a greengage. Barch picked one, split it, smelled of the pulp. "Rather like lemon verbena, or bay turn."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said in practical tones. "It's likely to be poisonous."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch smelled again, doubtfully. "One can't hurt me too much..."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "It might make you sick."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Then we'll know it's poison; there's nothing like the empirical method." He bit into the sac, chewed thoughtfully. "It doesn't taste very good."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Look," said Komeitk Lelianr. "There's that flying thing again."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch dropped the thorn-berry, watched the owl-headed, bat-winged, heron-legged creature slide to an awkward landing along the shore of the lake.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "If we can catch him," said Barch, "we'll have roast owl." He bent, picked up a rock, moved cautiously forward.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The owl-bat-heron waded out into the lake\emdash stopped short, one leg high in the air. The leg jerked forward, jerked back up; a black shape twisted through the air, fell into the thorny thicket.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That looks like a fish," exclaimed Barch. The bird stalked toward his catch. Barch ran forward, waving his arms. "No you don't." Gingerly he picked the black fish out of the thorns, while the owl-bat-heron scuttled back into the water. Komeitk Lelianr watched with distaste.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch tossed her his cigarette lighter. "You build a fire, I'll clean this thing."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He set it on a flat rock beside the river, sawed off head and tail with a sharp flake of stone. Gritting his teeth, he split open the soft belly, pulled, scraped, washed, and eventually had two strips of leathery white flesh.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk had started a fire by the edge of the forest; Barch secured a pair of green twigs, carefully roasted the fish for them.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "There," he said, "that smells pretty good." He laid the fish on a rock, licked his fingers. "It even tastes good."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr ate without comment.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's not too filling," said Barch, "but we won't starve today." He looked back to the green thorn-berries. "They didn't taste good\emdash but I don't feel any pangs yet." He covered over the fire. "Now we'd better explore."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A distant explosion jarred the air. Echoes rumbled away down the valley. "What's that?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr stood listening. "Probably there's a stone quarry somewhere over a mountain."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch anxiously scanned the mountainside. "We've got to explore, find out where the nearest settlement is, if there is one."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And then what?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We'll know more when we see how the land lies. If we could steal one of those barges somehow we might..." His voice trailed off into silence. He caught Komeitk Lelianr, pulled her down behind a thorn-bush. "Quiet!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Across the lake three men stood like pillars of gray rock.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "They've seen us," whispered Komeitk Lelianr.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't think so. I saw them come out of the forest."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "If they come around this way, they'll see us."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "They're coming." Barch took round heavy stones in each hand, waited tensely for them.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\par
\pard\sl-250\slmult0\qc\f1\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 CHAPTER V \f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\par
\f0\fs18 Two of the men were dark-skinned, with faces thin and foxlike; the third was lemon-yellow, with a flat round face, orange eyebrows tufted like horns. They moved with a soft stealthy tread that suggested the wariness of deer.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "They've got bows and arrows," muttered Barch. "They can't be either slaves or keepers."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Perhaps they're fugitives too," said Komeitk Lelianr.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The men drew closer, the sound of their voices came across the marsh. Through the thorns Barch could see every detail of their faces, their clothes. Twenty yards away they stopped short, turned to look down the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Faint in the distance came a sound like a bugle call, then another from a different direction, then another, startlingly close. The three men hissed in sudden fright, bounded off up the hillside, disappeared under the blanket of black fronds.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch uneasily rose to his feet, looked across the lake.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Whatever it is, it's certainly not good. We'd better leave too."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr seized his ankle. "Get down," she whispered, "Podruods!"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch dropped flat on his face. Out of the forest sprang a lithe red figure. He stood poised, raised his spiked head, called; bugle tones rang across the lake.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He waited. Answering calls like hunting horns returned from the distance.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Podruod stood like a statue; Barch and Komeitk Lelianr hugged the marshy ground.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was a crashing of branches, thudding of hasty feet. A fat man with a conical tuft of pink hair stumbled into the clearing. He saw the Podruod, froze like a bird. The Podruod watched him without moving a muscle. The fat man cautiously started to slip around the lake. The Podruod made a leap forward, halted. Barch thought of a cat with a mouse.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Podruod once more raised his head, again the brass voice rang out. Behind the fat man two more Podruods jumped into the clearing. The fat man ran frantically, panting and groaning.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A shadow passed over Barch's head; he looked up with a convulsive jerk that hurt his neck. It was a raft ten feet long, four feet wide, carrying a Klau. If the Klau had looked down he might have seen Barch and Komeitk Lelianr, but his eyes were on the fat man.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Under the raft hung a dark mass, like a bundle of clothes; as the raft slid forward it unfolded, lowered arms like lengths of black hose. They coiled around the fugitive's chest, his legs, his ankles. He stumbled, fell into the thorn-bushes where he lay kicking, thrashing, screaming like a horse.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The raft moved slowly on, dragged him through the bushes, across the mud, into the lake. He sank out of sight. The surface of the lake rippled and boiled. The raft rose; the fat man now hung limp. He was covered with round brown cups. One by one they dropped away, splashed back into the lake. Barch recognized the stinger-mollusks which had jarred his arm. He squeezed himself even flatter into the ground.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The black arms contracted, the fat man was hoisted up; a black mantle dropped in limp folds around him, pinched in at the bottom, became a tight bag.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The raft rose, slid quietly down the valley. Barch turned to look for the Podruods. They had vanished.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He lay flaccid for a moment, then nudged Komeitk Lelianr. In a husky whisper he said, "Let's run for the trees."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 They hurriedly climbed the hill. Long red-veined black fronds fell around them like weeping willows. They could not see, they could not be seen. On the heavy humus their feet made no sound. Every moment or so Barch stopped to listen. Silence.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Light punctured the wall of fronds. The hillside leveled off, dipped into a basin. The humus thinned, revealing chalky white marl underneath.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch heard a quick breath; he spun on his heel. Behind stood a grinning Podruod with a shaved head, wearing a black breechclout and black boots. Slowly, with a fanciful flourish he extended his arm; a sliver of bright steel nearly touched Barch's chest. Barch's eyes shifted behind to a second man, slender, yellowish-white of skin, who had seized Komeitk Lelianr's arms from behind.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch hesitated. The Podruod's metallic voice rang out peremptorily. Barch made no reply. He spoke again, this time with harsh emphasis. Barch saw the muscles tense to stab; dimly heard Komeitk Lelianr answering in the same tongue. The Podruod relaxed, sheathed his rapier; death moved back a pace.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Podruod turned to Komeitk Lelianr, looked her over, up and down. He spoke again; Komeitk Lelianr replied.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "What's he saying?" Barch demanded.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said in a distant voice, "They want to know if there are any more of us. They're escaped slaves too. The Podruod must be a criminal of some sort."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Oh." Barch relaxed. "Is that all?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said noncommittally, "Most of it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "What do you mean?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "There seems to be a kind of tribe living up here." She nodded at the Podruod. "He's the chief."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Podruod's inspection of Komeitk Lelianr suddenly aroused Barch's apprehension. He said in a hurried monotone, "Throw on the power in your shoes. He's not holding you tightly; you can break away. I'll take off down hill."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Before Komeitk Lelianr had a chance to answer, the Podruod, with a quick motion, unsheathed his blade. He motioned on ahead, pushed Barch's shoulder with a heavy hand.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Rage overcame Barch; he swung a punch. The Podruod grinned, ducked back. The sliver of steel gleamed in the air; he lunged playfully; a quarter inch of steel stabbed Barch's shoulder. Pale with anger and frustration Barch jerked back.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Roy," cried Komeitk Lelianr, "be sensible! Obey him, or you'll be killed!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "He's got his eyes on you," panted Barch. "Once we get in that cave\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The steel menaced again; the Podruod barked out roughly. With an agonizing sickness in the pit of his stomach, Barch stumbled forward.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 They crossed an open flat, climbed a little slope to the wall of a sheer limestone cliff. The yellowish-white man motioned Komeitk Lelianr into a shadowed indentation. At the far end Barch saw a narrow crevice. The first man and Komeitk Lelianr slid into the crevice. Barch followed, groped along a short irregular passage, stumbled into a low-ceilinged hall close after the girl.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Smoky yellow lamps and a blazing fire gave off warm light; there were two rough tables, benches, the smell of food and bodies. Twenty or thirty men and women were visible; others came blinking curiously out of dark corners.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch stood tensely, his eyes on Komeitk Lelianr. The chief was giving directions to a pair of men in gray; he turned, called across the cave to where a pot bubbled on the fire. He stood three inches more than six feet: a magnificent creature, wide, thick, without a spare ounce of flesh. His head was shaved; he had hard bony features, and walked in his heavy black boots as lightly as Lekthwans walked on air-sandals. Barch looked anxiously back to Komeitk Lelianr. She watched the chief; the lamplight reflected flickering in her eyes.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The chief walked over to her, put his hands on her shoulders. Barch charged forward, stopped a great open-handed slap. He punched, felt the numb jar of blows. Lamps, walls, fires, faces became a meaningless backdrop. The red face was intent, the nostrils flared. Barch twisted the face askew with a haymaker; the face twisted back without change of expression. Barch felt his wind going, his legs felt like logs, he could hardly raise his arms. "Ellen," he croaked, "grab a rock, brain him...."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr pressed back against the wall, turned her face away. Three great blows hit Barch. The first was like a lead hammer and the lights faded. The second was like a dark surf washing over him, the third was a rumble of distant thunder.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch awoke on a pile of skins. He sat up, feeling his face. It was puffy and ached dully. At a long table across the room three or four women pounded meal in stone mortars.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 At the end sat Komeitk Lelianr. She rose to her feet, bent over a pot, came to Barch with a crockery bowl. "Drink this and you'll feel better."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch started to speak, but the words choked in his throat. He took the bowl, drank. Komeitk Lelianr stood watching. Barch stared at her coldly. "How're you making out with the chief?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Clet?" She shrugged.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You speak his same language I notice."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's a common tongue that everyone knows."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch handed back the bowl, turned his head to the wall. A few minutes later he rose to his feet, staggered outside, leaned against the cliff, vomited.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Raising his head again, he saw a pair of gray men skirting the hillside, carrying a basket between them. Behind came Clet, the Podruod chief, a beast the size of a boar slung over his shoulder. His eyes fixed impassively on Barch, he strode inside the cave.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch settled himself upon a rock, rubbed his aching head. After a moment he raised his eyes, studied the expanse of the valley. It was shaped roughly like the Mediterranean Sea, with the cave at a position comparable to Libya. High mountains ringed the Levantine end; at Gibraltar the river cut through a narrow steep-walled notch; along the Cote d'Azur he noticed the entrance to a second valley. Directly opposite the cave, in the position of Italy, a great round-knobbed bluff reared up to dominate the valley. Strange, thought Barch, that the Klau maintain no fort up there. Looking closely he thought to see the outline of ruins.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Overcast scudded low over the mountains; a few drops of rain fell. Barch rose to his feet, shivered as a cold blast of wind penetrated the threadbare Modok garment.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He looked tentatively toward the entrance into the cave. The two men with the basket now sat beside it husking a kind of nut. One of them snapped his fingers at Barch, motioned.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch glowered, half-turned away. But, he decided, he would look less of a fool working than refusing to work. He could always leave the cave\emdash but why should he? He was free; he was fed and sheltered; there was no reason for him to go. Barch sat down, began hulling nuts.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Weeks passed, two, three, a month. Barch mastered the simple routines of the tribe, gained a smattering of the common tongue. On several occasions he went hunting, and once killed a large, brown, two-legged creature like a hybrid of kangaroo and lizard, for which we was warmly congratulated.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He explored the cave. Four different passages opened out of the community hall. Two struck off more or less horizontally, winding through small chambers, nooks, niches and alcoves wherein the tribesmen slept. A third led down past Clet's chamber, dropping into the depths under the mountain. The fourth served as a flue for the fire, led up into an enormous space over the hall called Big Hole. At one end, where the wall was barely a shell, daylight seeped in through a fissure. Stalactites hung, stalagmites rose, occasionally joining to form spindly columns of fascinating height. In Big Hole, Barch arranged his bed of humus and rudely cured hides.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The tribe numbered thirty-four: twenty-one men, ten women, three doubtfuls. These last were the Calbyssinians: Armian, Ardl, Arn, whose sex was a frantically guarded secret. They were slight, pretty creatines with melting blue eyes and purple-gold hair. They bundled themselves in loose cloaks, and spent all their leisure time trying to probe out each other's secret. Their hints, wiles, sly strategies provided Barch with almost his only amusement.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 In addition to the Calbyssinians, there were four Byathids: three tall pink men with foxy eyes, droopy noses, silky cinnamon-colored hair; one pink raw-boned woman with a voice like a sheep.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was Kerbol and his dour woman, stocky and gray-green, with pointed heads and frog-like faces.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There were three hatchet-faced Splangs with skins like Cordovan leather: Chevrr, Skurr and a thin beetle-faced woman that they shared.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There were two Griffits, cat-like men with watchful, sidelong eyes, stiff mustaches and an air of vindictive truculence that never quite manifested itself.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was a large brown man who had lost his nose; his name was Flatface. He controlled two bald and bad-tempered women of unguessable race.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was Pedratz, taffy-colored and smelling of musk, with eyebrows that rose into fantastic horns. There was Moranko, a sullenly handsome youth who hated Clet and presently Barch. There was the dwarf, Moses, with a punchinello face and skin like a piebald horse.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There were six of the bulldog-faced Modoks; four men and two women. They crouched by themselves at the back of the hall, watching everything with wide, suspicious eyes.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was Sl, a white-skinned man with white bifurcated beard and split nose who did everything double; there was the musician, Lkandeli Szet. There was Barch; there was Komeitk Lelianr; there was Clet and his two women: a pair of young nondescripts who had been the original property of Lkandeli Szet.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Making a mental inventory, Barch estimated that at least fifteen races from as many worlds occupied the cave. Sitting quietly at the back bench, he considered the melange with wry amusement. Never would it be said that his life had been uneventful or drab.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 On Earth no one even suspected the existence of Magarak. And yet by this time ... With a queasiness in his stomach, he speculated on the Klau raid. What had been their purpose?\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Across the hall the voices of Flatface's two bald women rose in acrimony. Clet, at the big table in front of the fire, raised his bony red head; the bickering quieted. Clet disliked noise. Here was one reason, thought Barch, for the fact that the tribe so widely disparate in background could live in comparative amity. Another lay in the fundamental nature of their existence, a kind of cultural least-common-denominator, a stage through which each of the races had passed. For Barch, that stage had been only three or four thousand years in the past. He glanced at Komeitk Lelianr, who sat drawing aimless patterns on the table with her fingers. How long had it been since her ancestors lived in caves? A hundred thousand years? A million?\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She looked clean and fresh, Barch noticed. Her face was thinner; her mouth had lost something of its girlish curve. Her expression was abstracted, distant, the result of a stoic or fatalistic characterization, no doubt.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch rose to his feet, went outside into the darkness. Mist that was not quite drizzle dampened his face. Against the blurred gray of the limestone cliff he noticed a dark shape. His heart stopped for an instant, then started again. It was Kerbol, whom nature had endowed with a skin the color of wet rock, pop-eyes, a mouth like a flap. Barch remembered that Kerbol grumbled about the heat in the hall and seemed to enjoy the cool dampness of the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch went to stand beside him; any man that preferred the solitude of the valley to the hall seemed an ally.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol grunted, and after a moment said in a deep rumbling voice, "The mist falls, the wind blows backwards down Palkwarkz Ztvo. Tomorrow the sky will be high and then the Klau come hunting. Tomorrow will be a good day to stay close by the cave."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch remembered the bugling Podruods, the frantic fat man, the Klau raft with the black arms dangling below. "How often do the Klau hunt?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Every eight, ten days, if the weather suits. They are the Quodaras District Klau; Parkwarkz Ztvo is their region. The Xolboar Klau hunt in Poriflammes." He pointed to the valley entering the Palkwarkz Ztvo near the mouth.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Sudden enlightenment came to Barch. "So\emdash we live in a hunting preserve; we're tolerated in order to provide the Klau with sport!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The Klau planet is a week distant; the Klau must amuse themselves."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said thoughtfully, "I could certainly amuse myself hunting Podruods and Klau."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol digested the idea. "You think in strange directions. Very strange."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch laughed sourly. "I don't see anything strange about it. If the Klau hunt me, it's only fair that I hunt them."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That is not the theory of the hunt." Kerbol spoke politely.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's not the Klau theory; it is my theory. Do we have to live by Klau theory?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol said thoughtfully, "It was too hot at the quarry."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A dull explosion from over Kebali Ridge jarred the air of the valley. "There they shoot now," said Kerbol. "Notice the double shock?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The charge was ten cans of abiloid, a twentieth cut of the super. The super smashes the rock; the abiloid pushes it down."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You seem to know a great deal about explosives."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol nodded gloomily. "Five years I drilled and charged, drilled and charged. And always in the heat. I ran into the forest and came over Mount Kebali to Palkwarkz Ztvo, where I must take my chances with the hunters."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch asked curiously, "What is that black thing that hangs under the Klau raft?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Those are"\emdash Kerbol stopped, grasped for a word\emdash "pulling things. In factories they lift loads. The Klau grow them; they are half-alive."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The Klau carry other weapons?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yes. They shoot across long distances; a little splinter enters a man's belly, explodes. The man is dead."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked up and down the dark valley. The mist had risen, a current of air smelling of rotting vegetation blew on his face. From the far distance sounded a harsh clanking, a screech. Barch muttered, "At night a whole regiment of Podruods could come up here."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol moved uneasily. "That has never happened."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "But it might," said Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You think strange, uncomfortable thoughts," said Kerbol.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 On the following day the overcast was high, the wind light. The tribesmen hung close to the cave. But no bugling cries were heard and the Klau did not appear.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The next day was the same, with a near calm across the valley. Again the men of the tribe ventured only a few hundred yards from the cliff, and at the evening meal there was only a few scrapings of gruel in the pot.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The third day dawned blustery, with ragged gray clouds breaking over Mount Kebali like surf over a sea-wall.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Clet ordered Flatface, Barch, the Modoks and the Calbyssinians out to grub for meal-nuts, while the remaining men filed into the forest to hunt meat.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The bugling of the Podruods sounded an hour later. Barch and the Calbyssinians jumped up, seized the half-filled bags, hurried back around the hillside.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Across the valley rang the hunting cries, converging near the dominating bluff; looking over his shoulder Barch glimpsed the ominous dark shadow of the Klau raft.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The hunters came filing back to the cave one at a time, wide-eyed with exhaustion.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Across the valley the bugle calls suddenly ceased. Standing in the crevice Barch saw the black raft slipping down the valley toward the notch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Four hunters had not yet returned: Clet, Moranko, the two Splangs, Chevrr and Skurr.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Clet slipped in first, his bony red face impassive. Then came Moranko carrying a dead creature that looked like a wooly caterpillar. Minutes passed. Chevrr crossed the flat. He muttered a few words to Clet, jerked his thumb across the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Skurr, the Splang, had been hunted down and killed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 On sudden impulse Barch dropped into the seat opposite to where Clet sat whetting his knife. "I think we should do something about these hunts."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Clet turned him a brief cool glance, returned to his work. Steel rasped on stone, lamplight flickered and winked on the metal as the big red hands methodically stroked. Barch raised his voice: "We don't necessarily need to skulk around this valley." He paused; Clet showed no interest.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Trying to keep anger out of his voice, Barch said, "Every week somebody else gets killed."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "More always come," said Clet. "Too many in the cave is not good."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Next time the Klau hunt, they might get you\emdash or me." Clet shrugged. "We should hunt them instead\emdash kill the Podruods, kill the Klau."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, no," said Clet impatiently. "Then a warship comes down to kill us all. We live good now, hey?" He laughed complacently. "Food, women, hey? Same way for many, many years. Best not to change."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch rose slowly to his feet, staring in frustration down at Clet, who glanced up impassively, then returned to his whetstone.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\par
\fs18 CHAPTER VI \f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\par
\b\scaps\f0\fs18 Five \b0\scaps0 days passed, low angry days full of rain and stormy gusts that tilled Big Hole with eery whistling sounds.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 The sixth day was quiet, with a high overcast rippled with fish-scale black. Barch found Clet eating his breakfast of toasted meat and gruel cake. "Today the Klau might come again. If we went down to the notch, and hid where they enter the valley\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Clet shook his head stubbornly, at the same time gnawing a bone.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr knelt by the fire, tending the gruel cakes which baked on a hot rock. She turned her head, spoke shortly. "Don't argue with him, Roy; he's very single-minded."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Clet looked up. "What does she say?" He dropped the bone, put his wide red hands on the table.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked down at him in disgust. Blood raced through his body. He felt strong. His voice came out harsh and deep. "Maybe you want to live in a cave all your life like an animal!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Clet's eyes gleamed under the black eyebrows; he seemed to be listening not to Barch so much as to an inner secret voice.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "There's ways of leaving Magarak, if we'd work together."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Clet grunted contemptuously, turned back to his bone. "Now comes the crazy talk."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch was taken aback. "Crazy talk?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Clet's big white teeth glittered in a grin. He flourished the bone toward Komeitk Lelianr. "She told me much about you," he said. "You are a crazy man; you would fly through the space like a magician." His voice rose, his eyes glittered. "Now, no more crazy talk; this is Palkwarkz Ztvo, I am Clet."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch slowly went to the mouth of the cave, took his bow and quiver of arrows.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Ho!" Clet called gruffly. "Where do you go?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "None of your damn business."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 From back in the cave came the sudden scrape of the bench; Barch saw Clet reaching for his own bow. He ducked out the cave mouth, ran across the open space. He glimpsed Clet standing in the crevice like a heroic statue of Mars: bow bent, arrow tense with imminent mission. Barch flung himself to the ground; the arrow sang over his head. He rose, dodged into the trees where he pulled an arrow into bis own bow, waited, pale and shaking.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 After a careless survey of the valley, Clet returned inside the cave.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch walked morosely down-slope under the flapping fronds. An inglorious exit, he thought. He stopped, looked back toward the cave. He recalled the first time he had seen Komeitk Lelianr, stepping jauntily from the circus-striped space-ball. If she had noticed him at all, it had been as part of the local scene, a native. He felt a sudden glimmer of insight into her mind. Poor devil, thought Barch, she even found Earth food revolting.... Well, that was all water under the bridge. And now what? Probably, after Clet's temper had run its course, he could return to the cave. And so the years would pass, while he grew older and his fire died out.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 No, said Barch, not if he died today under the Klau raft. He turned, ran at a half-trot to the notch at the valley mouth. He climbed the left-hand slope, settled himself at the narrowest spot.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Time passed. Wind blew chill down the valley, a rim of black clouds loomed past Mount Kebali. A drop touched his nose; only one. The rain hung off in indecision. A poor day to expect the Klau.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Then he heard the scrape of boots, the soft clang of Podruod voices. Barch tingled with primeval emotion. He sat up straighter, eased his muscles.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Eight Podruods came trotting into the valley, light as dancers in their black boots. Cuirasses covered their chests, black hair-spikes vibrated with each step. A cushioned raft followed, floating three feet off the ground. A young Klau in maroon harness sat fingering a pair of weapons on a rack. He halted the raft, glanced easily around the valley. Barch glimpsed the blood-red stars in his eyes.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Klau touched controls with his feet, jumped to the ground, stretched. Negligently he conferred with the Podruod sergeant, studied the contours of the valley, pointed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Six Podruods moved quietly off into the black fronds. Two remained behind, squatting a little distance up the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Klau languidly took up one of his weapons\emdash it looked much like a long-barreled automatic, thought Barch\emdash  and balanced it in his hand.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch eased himself into position. He stretched the bow.... Now! The arrow hummed down, plunged into the back of the black head.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch crashed down the slope, sprang to the raft, reached across the black body, seized the weapons.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Podruods said, "Oh!"\emdash a soft hiss of outrage and horror.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch aimed, pressed the trigger. Nothing. The Podruods loped forward, mouths open in contortions of great rage. Barch clawed a lever, perhaps a safety lock. He pressed the trigger; the first sprawled on his face. Barch pressed again; the second fell.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch listened. Silence except for the murmur of the river, a distant sound of snapping foliage. Now what? He seized the Klau's maroon harness, dragged the body into the undergrowth. He turned to the raft, seated himself; it bounced like a boat under his weight. He put his feet into the controls, experimented.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The raft shook, dodged back and forth, rose up on an alarming slant. Barch pulled away his feet; the raft sank slowly. Once more he tried and presently brought the raft back to the mouth of the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He jumped to the ground, inspected the horrid black bundle under the raft. He took a knife from one of the Podruods, cut at the two bands which held the thing against the raft. It fell to the ground with a sodden spongy sound. Barch gave it a cautious kick, rolled it over, down into the river, where it expanded, opened, lay flaccid.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The next problem was how to deal with the six Podruods still in the valley. He rode the raft up the wall of the notch, settled where he had kept his original vigil. He waited an hour with complete patience. The wind had lost its bite, the sky was high and mild.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A quarter mile up the valley he saw the Podruods, apparently confused by the Klau's ineptitude. Barch laughed quietly. A few minutes later they came diffidently along the valley floor. At the Podruod corpses, they stopped in great puzzlement, looking in all directions. Barch aimed, fired swiftly six times. Six men fell as if playing a nursery game.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch descended, dragged the bodies into the foliage. The next hunting party might or might not notice the odor of carrion; at the moment Barch did not care especially.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He climbed aboard the raft, flew low over the treetops up the valley. A hundred yards from the cave he moored the raft, jumped to the ground. Cautiously he approached the crevice. One of the Modok women, fetching water, looked up without interest. Barch nodded to Kerbol who sat outside scraping at a bow, entered the cave.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Clet looked negligently from the table. "Here is the crazy man, back from his hunting." He put his big red hands flat on the table, started to rise.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch lifted the gun, pressed the trigger. Clet fell forward. Tough on Clet.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Women were screaming in surprise and terror; Flatface bellowed in outrage; after a quick look the Modoks darted white-faced from the hall. Barch said in a voice as casual as he could contrive, "Call everybody in here. I'm running this outfit now and I've got something to say."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The cave gradually filled with whispering figures. Barch sat on the table, with his feet on the bench. He looked around the cave. Thirty-two in the tribe with Clet and Skurr dead.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He considered what he had to say\emdash a problem in polemics that would daunt anyone. Thirteen different races, thirty-one different brains; thirteen basic mental patterns, thirty-one sub-varieties. An idea which aroused one would leave another indifferent.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "One thing is important," he began. "I did not kill Clet because I hated him. Clet is dead because he was stupid. Clet had to die because he had the mind of a slave. Under Clet you slunk around the hills like animals. The Klau came each week; each week someone was hunted along the valley and killed. In not too many weeks everyone here might expect to be hunted to death."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Now, there will be a difference. We are no longer slaves; we are men. When the Podruods come into the valley we will kill them. There is no need to run. We have bows, we have arrows, we will kill."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Hah!" The exhalation came from one of the Griffits, who stood twirling his little whiskers.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "But this is only incidental. The main thing is escape. I want to leave Magarak. I want to return home. You others, do you wish for your homes?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was a mutter of low voices.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol rumbled stolidly, "You speak wild words. We cannot fly space like moon-dragons."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "There is no way," bawled Flatface.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Both of you are wrong," said Barch politely. "A few months ago a dozen Lenape escaped. There are a hundred ways. This is my idea." He paused. There was complete silence. "We will steal a barge, build an air-tight compartment upon it. We will load on food and stores, and leave Magarak behind us. The plan is as simple as that. There are difficulties; they must be overcome. The plan is not impossible. We have nothing to lose; are we not already condemned to death by the Klau?\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "When we leave Magarak, we will fly for the nearest friendly planet. We will be a long time in space; eventually we will arrive. But from the moment we leave Magarak, we are no longer slaves, or fugitives; we are space-travelers. And when we arrive, we will be heroes, and we will have much to tell our friends and our families."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Once more he looked around the circle of faces. How could they help but alight to his enthusiasm? They must be as eager as he to leave Magarak.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Chevrr, the hatchet-faced Splang, snapped, "Talk is easy. Where will we find materials and tools?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch laughed. "Those are the problems which lie ahead of us. There will be many problems; there will be much work and danger. But if things go well, we will win. What do we have to lose? By acting instead of existing, we stop being animals; we become men."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Where can we work on such a barge?" came Kerbol's bass rumble. "It will be seen from the air. The Klau will land a crew and fly it away."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "One place I know of," said Barch, "is Big Hole. The outside wall is a shell; light comes in through fissures. We will break an opening, slide the barge through, then pile rocks back up. Now what do you say? I cannot build a spaceship alone; are you with me?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Looking around the faces, he saw passivity, confusion, stupidity. He also saw, here and there, glimmerings of hope, imagination, enthusiasm.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol rumbled, "It is worth trying. We lose nothing. We will try."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Good," said Barch with a tight smile. "I see you are all with me. But in case"\emdash he looked casually down at the sprawled red body of Clet\emdash "any others think like Clet, now they should speak."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 No one spoke.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Excellent," said Barch with a rather broader smile. He jumped down to the floor. "First things first. Before we liberate a barge we need a place to hide it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He took up a lamp, climbed the passage into Big Hole. The tribe hesitated, then one by one followed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Damp gray walls glistened in the yellow light; shadows sagged and danced. Where the passage came up from the hall, the floor was almost level in an area a hundred feet square. Ridges of agate jutted up at the opposite end, where the wall was thin.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch crossed to the far wall, climbed up the loose detritus. "Here is where we'll open out. Quite a job but it's got to be done."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol grunted. "With a few cans of abiloid I could blast a hole as easy as husking a nut."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch considered him thoughtfully. "You worked at the stone quarry over the hill. Do you know where they keep the explosives?" Kerbol grunted.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tonight," said Barch, "you and I will visit the stone quarry"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Night had filled Palkwarkz Ztvo for two hours when Barch and Kerbol climbed aboard the Klau raft. Mist blew on their faces as the raft rose; the mountainside below was featureless as crumpled black cloth, except for a single spark of light, winking on the flat before the cave.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol touched Barch's arm. "Over there, up over Mount Kebali; then down."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch nodded. Mount Kebali loomed ahead like an underwater reef, and down on the slope appeared a lonesome cluster of lights. Far beyond lay the luminous blur that was Quodaras District.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Kerbol," said Barch to the dark shape behind him, "in this project we've got to trust each other like brothers\emdash and also take sensible precautions. What, in your opinion, are the chances of someone in the tribe betraying us to the Klau?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol made a rumbling sound. "The chances are nonexistent. The traitor would gain nothing. The Klau would not take such a crazy tale seriously; the tale-bearer would be sent to the arsenic mines as an escaped slave. True," he went on, "there are some with small urge to leave Palkwarkz Ztvo; life on their home worlds is no better. On the other hand, some highly-ranked planets are represented in the tribe\emdash my own, Perdu, Calbys, Koethena, Lekthwa." He paused. Barch said nothing.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol spoke on, "I will be glad to see my home village; it lies in the plain of Sponis, which is blue with turf and runner lichen, and there runs the river Erth."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Earth?" said Barch. "That is the name of my planet."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Earth?" Kerbol rolled the word on his tongue. "I have never heard of it." He ruminated a moment. "You must be wild and fanciful dreamers on Earth. I have slaved twelve years on Magarak, lived a free man in Palkwarkz Ztvo for two; never have I known anything so daring."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It seems to me the first thing a man would think of."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The lights of the stone quarry shifted, spread slowly apart like the opening of a marvelous bright night-flower. Barch looked down at the quarry. "They must work all night."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The quotas are hard; much stone goes for ocean reclamation. Notice," Kerbol pointed, "that north face is next on schedule; they drill now for blasting. And there"\emdash once more he pointed\emdash "is the explosive's depot. The barge comes loaded, slides into the depot; empty, it slides out, and in slides a new load."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And what precautions are taken?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol shrugged. "First, an electrified fence which we will fly over. If there are alarm lines, we will avoid them also. Inside the warehouse will be a few Podruods, gaming or asleep, and Bornghaleze dispatchers who load orders onto an outgoing belt."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We'll take them as they come."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The raft dropped, the quarry lights expanded. Ticking of hammers, intermittent grate of machinery came loud across the damp night. Bright blue points of fire showed where torches melted blast-pockets into rock. On the roof of the warehouse were outlined four dull squares of light-ventilation cupolas.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch lowered the raft to the roof, stepped off, walked carefully to a cupola. He eased his head into the light, looked down. He felt a tread behind him: Kerbol. Barch said, "There's nothing here; The place is clean, empty."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol bent his head. "True," he muttered. "There's not even a sack of blow powder." He straightened, looked at the rock face a half-mile away, then bent his head over the ventilator again. "Even the barge is gone."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch eyed the sky. "How soon will new supplies get here?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol shrugged. "Tomorrow, tonight..."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Look," said Barch, "those red lights."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "That's the new load."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Come on," said Barch. He sprinted to the raft. "What now?" asked Kerbol, as Barch swung the raft into the air.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Maybe we'll get more done tonight than we bargained for." He pushed the speed pedal down hard, swept out wide, circled, approached the barge from the stern. "Where's the pilot?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol pointed. "In the dome at the prow."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Be ready with your gun." He skimmed in over the barge, dropped to the deck. "I'll take the pilot, you handle the rest of the ship." He ran stealthily forward; the pilot was a sharp-featured silhouette, eyes on the lighted rectangle of the warehouse. Barch wrenched open the door to the dome.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Take the barge up\emdash quick!" He pointed the gun. The pilot, a beady-eyed little man with a thin, dark face cast a startled look over his shoulder. Barch said, "Quick\emdash up!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot turned reluctantly to the controls. "I must follow my schedule, or the dispatcher will\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You're a dead man," growled Barch, "unless we're moving up right now!" He jabbed hard with the gun barrel. "Up!"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "We're going up!" said the pilot peevishly.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Faster!" Barch looked over the side. "Now, back the way you came."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 The barge swept away from the quarry. "Now\emdash out with those side lights," said Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'm not allowed to," protested the pilot. "It's punishable offense."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch grinned, tapped him on the back of the skull with the gun barrel. "Out with the lights!" He looked quickly over his shoulder. "Any crew aboard?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No crew. I load at Phrax District chemical complex, discharge at the warehouse."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "What's your cargo?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Explosives, general supplies."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Barch heard footsteps: Kerbol looked in.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\tx4579\f0\fs18 "All in order?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Nobody aboard."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Good." Barch backed out of the dome, motioned Kerbol in. "You steer him; you know the lay of the land."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch went over by the edge of the barge, looked out into the darkness. Step one. Achievement. He felt the bulwark-cold hard metal, the same hard metal which one day would lift him clear of Magarak out into great space.\f1\fs24\par
