\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 CHAPTER VII \f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\par
\b\scaps\f0\fs18 The \b0\scaps0 barge slid up the slopes of Mount Kebali. The sounds of the quarry faded; the lights contracted to a tight cluster. The sea of trembling luminescence, the factories, furnaces, mills and yards of Quodaras District now lay astern.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Barch circled the catwalk, looked into the dome. "Faster!" The barge lurched under his feet; he staggered back into the cargo. The craft has quite a power plant, he thought\emdash all to the good if they reached space.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Moisture suddenly sprayed his face; they were driving through fine rain. He stumbled up into the lee of the dome.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The rain stopped, the barge broke out of the mist into a biting wind. Palkwarkz Ztvo lay below, a dark wilderness. Barch strained his eyes for the wan flicker of light. Like a faint star at the horizon, it eluded him. He put his head into the dome, asked Kerbol, "Can you see our light?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol pointed. "There." He nudged the pilot. "Land beside that light."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Impossible," muttered the pilot. "We are over Palkwarkz Ztvo\emdash wild-man country. They'll put us in their pots."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, they won't," said Barch. "Land beside the light."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge sank. Blackness reached up past them; there was a crash, a snapping of foliage. The raft reached ground.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked warily out into the darkness. All was quiet. He turned to the pilot. "Get out."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot hesitated, clinging to the protection of his dome. "What are you going to do with me?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Nothing."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot jumped, made a quick dash for the underbrush. Barch tackled him around the knees; both fell into the soggy humus. Barch rose, seized the man by the collar of his jacket, marched him back past the barge, up the slope. Kerbol came after like a stealthy gray bear.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch entered the hall with the pilot. The entire tribe was huddled around the great table talking heatedly; Barch stood watching the play of firelight on the un-Earthly features.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was a hiss, the talk halted; faces swung around as if operated by a lever.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch gave the pilot to Kerbol. "Lower him into one of the potholes on a rope." He turned back to the big table. "We've two or three hours work outside. Let's get it over with. Bring out your knives and axes."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was uneasy movement, slow uncomfortable rising to the feet. Barch watched impassively.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Flatface said in a surly voice, "Work is for daytime. This is night. Let the work wait." The others watched anxiously, poised and uncertain as rabbits.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 This was the first test, the most important. Barch made no sudden move. He waited, let the suspense build up. Flatface nervously glanced at Barch's gun. Barch said softly, "Where is your axe, Flatface?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Flatface motioned to the wall. "There it lies."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\i\f0\fs18 "Get \b\fs20 it!"\b0\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Flatface slowly gained his feet. Barch jumped two quick steps forward. There was a startled swaying back. "Everybody! Outside!" He took the two lamps, went to the entrance, waited while the tribesmen filed out past him.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 In the lamplight the barge was a large dark shape, vastly more impressive than words Barch could have used inside the cave. "There's your spaceship."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 The tribesmen muttered with awe, excitement.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-202\slmult0\f0\fs18 "Tomorrow we'll unload the cargo, but tonight we've got to cover it over with branches so it can't be seen from above."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch pulled himself up from his couch with the first glimmer of light. He pulled on the Modok smock, went out to inspect the barge. It seemed to fill half the flat, like a whale in the front yard.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 To check the camouflage he mounted the raft, floated up into the sky. The forest was a matted black tangle, the barge an extension of the same tangle. Satisfied, he dropped back to the ground.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 It was essential that the Klau remained ignorant of his plans. He must avoid giving them provocation. In one sense, killing the Klau yesterday was a mistake. But it had been necessary\emdash an act which had given him an aura of power that killing Clet ten times would have failed to do. In the future he might have to back down on some of his fire-eating threats. Avoid the Podruods as best as possible; fight if cornered.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He circled the barge. The seamless hull rose four feet over his head. He tried to visualize a super-structure, and achieved only the picture of a deck-house on a sea-going freighter.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He climbed aboard. About half the cargo was crates of various sizes. Toward the bow lay four bundles of heavy pipe, a half-dozen mechanisms, apparently drill torches, a dozen spools of smooth cable. A good haul, thought Barch. He revised his mental picture from a deck-house to a dome of air-tight fabric over the barge, held down against air pressure by a net of cables.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 He jumped to the ground, returned to the hall. Standing by the fire, he watched the women set out pots of gruel to boil.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol came blinking into the room, followed by the dour woman who was his mate. Barch felt a sudden sense of warmth, companionship. He had at least one friend in Palkwarkz Ztvo.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 After breakfast he took Kerbol out to the barge, to inspect the cargo. Kerbol snapped open a crate marked with black and red symbols; inside were cannisters the size of apples.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Those are abiloid," said Kerbol, "a slow explosive. This" \emdash he opened a smaller crate, which held dense semi-metallic bars supported on a red plastic rack\emdash "is super."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Super\emdash what?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol shrugged. "Super is what they call it at the quarry. A small cut of super is equal to ten crates of abiloid. But it's fast. It smashes. Abiloid pushes."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I hope you can detonate them."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol picked out one of the cans of abiloid, touched a wisp of thread. "This is the three minute timer. To detonate the super, you set it under a can of abiloid."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's all yours," said Barch. "There are you torches. Pick yourself a helper and open out Big Hole."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch returned to the cave, sent Flatface out in charge of a hunting crew.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 At noon Kerbol reported the cave wall ready for firing. Barch doubtfully eyed the sky. Fog was creeping down the slope of Mount Kebali. "We'd better wait till dark. Then if any Klau fly over, the hole in the mountain won't hit them in the eye."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 By mid-afternoon, the fog shrouded Palkwarkz Ztvo. Barch signaled Kerbol. "Set off your shots."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A few minutes later six blasts sent streamers of mist flying.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch entered the hall, took the down passage past Clet's old chamber, leaned over the pit at whose bottom sat the pilot. "Feel like working?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot looked up sullenly. "Kill me and have done."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't want to kill you. I need your help. I wouldn't keep you in this hole if I thought you wouldn't run away."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot's face became instantly cheerful. "I have nowhere to go; I cast my lot with yours."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch grinned. "That's a sensible decision, quickly arrived at." He lowered the rope, the pilot jerked himself up nimbly.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch took him to the barge, pointed to the gap in Big Hole.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I want the barge inside."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot swung himself quickly into the dome. "The work of an instant."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch climbed aboard behind the pilot. "We'll fly in together."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "As you wish," said the pilot peevishly.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge rose off the ground, glided up the slope, inched inside the gap. Two fires burned on a level area at the far end. "Land between the two fires," said Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge slid through dimness. Stalactities, stalagmites clicked and crashed to the floor.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge grounded. Barch saw Kerbol already had men at work piling rocks back into the opening. He turned to the pilot. "How is it that the Klau trust you with a barge? Aren't they afraid you'll escape to the hills?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot made a supple gesture. "What would I gain? We pilots live well. In the hills the wild men eat each other like garfish."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch forebore to challenge the statement. "What would happen if you went back now?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\tx3763\f0\fs18 "I would be discredited."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Barch studied the pilot's mercurial face. "I don't want to kill you," he said slowly. "But I don't want the Klau to come looking for their barge."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Far from likely."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Unless you carried them tales."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot blew out his cheeks. "My loyalty is yours forever."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No one here but you knows how to pilot the barge. In a sense, you are essential to the success of our plan."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And what is this plan?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "There's no harm telling you. We'll build an airtight hatch over the barge and leave Magarak."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Ah." The pilot nodded. "Now, indeed, I will join you."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Now? Your previous promises could not have been sincere."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You misunderstand. We of Splang are very delicate in our meanings."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Chevrr up there is a Splang; I have no difficulty understanding him."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot hissed contemptuously. "He is the mountain stock, a crude uncouth race. We of the coast forests are a different people entirely."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Well, no matter," said Barch. "I'll take a chance on you. What's your name?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The pilot said something like, "T'ck-T'ck-T'ck."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'll call you Tick," said Barch. "You understand that \fs16 I'll \fs18 think poorly of any attempt to visit Quodaras?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Certainly. That's to be expected."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Then help fill the hole with rock. I'll talk more to you later."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch sat studying his list of the tribe members, a heterogeneous crew. Of men with technical skills useful in the conversion of a cargo barge to a space-ship, there was a depressing paucity. Pedratz claimed a knowledge of welding; Kerbol displayed familiarity with explosives; Tick could fly the barge. But who knew anything about air purification, who could repair drive-circuits, who knew the lore of space navigation?\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked unseeingly into the fire, drumming his fingers, thinking. The first thing to do was isolate the problems, work on each by itself. First, there must be greater security against the Klau. Barch critically inspected the opening to the cave, where nothing prevented Podruods from stepping in to kill them all.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He rose to his feet, walked through the winding crevice out into the night. Darkness everywhere. The wind roared down the valley, the great black leaves flapped a melancholy undertone, like surf on a rocky beach. Behind him the faintest glimmer of light shone out from the crevice.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tomorrow he would arrange some kind of trip-alarm system around the clearing. But there was still tonight. Barch returned within. Nearest the opening sat two Calbyssinians, Ardl and Arn busy at their incomprehensible love-making, each trying to divine the other's sex. Barch knelt beside them, took off his wrist watch. "Tonight we keep guard. You two will watch first, for as long as it takes this little finger to move from here to here. Then one of you will wake"\emdash he looked over his shoulder\emdash "the two Griffits. Come outside and I will show you where you must station yourselves. It's important."\f1\fs24\par
