\f0\fs18 Tick looked up in sudden wonder. Barch stepped forward, pulled up the front of his yellow blouse.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick's eyes popped forward until more was out than in. He writhed his shoulders; Kerbol and Flatface were dragged half across the table. He tensed his legs; incredibly Moranko was jerked a foot from the floor.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There on the sweating writhing skin was a flat brown spot. Barch pulled it free with his fingernails. Two objects dropped to the stone floor of the cave: a metal locket and the leech which humped sluggishly toward the fire. Tick leaned down at the locket, his eyes protruded as if on stalks. He drew his arms forward; Flatface and Kerbol, panting and gasping, came across the table like pillows. Barch picked up the locket, snapped it open, drew out a wisp of membrane.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tick," said Barch, "sit still."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick's eyes receded into his head. Kerbol and Flatface gained their feet.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tick," said Barch, "will you behave?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick sighed. "My life is no longer my own."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Not one of us here owns his life. We're in this together; we'll leave Magarak together or we'll die together. Do you understand that?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick made no answer. His eyes sought out Chevrr's, as if seeking sympathy.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said, "Where I go, your charm goes. When we get free of Magarak, you'll have it back."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick said nothing.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch returned the locator to the table, looked in at the pulsing pastel landscape. "What are those transparent white squares?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't know," said Tick.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "What are the black lines?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Those are the underground belts."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I see a bright orange spot with things like fish bones waving on top. How would I find out what place that is?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick looked. "That's on the Ptrsfur Peninsula, Zcham District."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "How do you know?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The signs are on the strip at the top."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And the orange block?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick twisted a knob. A black dot moved across the panorama, centered on the orange block. Tick pointed to a line of glowing orange symbols on the cylinder at the side. "There you will read the function of the block."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch scrutinized the symbols. "Can you read them?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch glanced around the room. "Ellen, can you read this?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Indifferently she came to look. "The manufacture of \i padisks verktt."\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And what is that?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 " 'Padisks' is number nine in series ten\emdash or eleven\emdash of the artificial elements. \i Verktt \i0 are a kind of radiation valves."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch grunted. "Oh." He tentatively turned the dial again. "This thing should be a big help to us." He looked around. No one appeared to be excited. "It's a great piece of luck."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Flatface pressed his agate eyes against -the slit, twisted the dial. "Ah\emdash there is the Purpurat, where I wound bobbins for five years."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch turned to Komeitk Lelianr. "Tick told me about a Magarak coordinator\emdash a calculating machine of some kind."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yes," said Komeitk Lelianr. "A manufacturing world is coordinated by what is called a 'brain'\emdash a scheduling machine, which keeps the elements of the world running efficiently."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She twisted the locator dial, reading the characters. Barch watched a moment. "Ellen, it looks like you've got yourself a job."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 She nodded in agreement. Barch glanced around the table. Eyes were on him; eyes black, blue, white, red, slate-green. He said hesitantly to the hall at large, "We might as well talk this project over."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He waited, there was no reply. They were, perhaps, not accustomed to talking things over.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We've got the barge," said Barch. "My idea was to fit on some kind of air-tight balloon, net it over with cable."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was silence. Barch looked around the table. Moses, the dwarf, threw wood on the fire. Barch said edgily, "I don't see why it wouldn't work, but I'm no spaceship engineer. Maybe somebody has a better idea."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said off-handedly, "Far simpler to obtain another barge, and weld the two of them face to face."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch sat perfectly still a moment, to make sure of himself. "That sounds like a very good idea." He paused. "There's \fs16 a \fs18 point to consider. In space we'll depend on the lift units for propulsion, so that we can keep to our feet. I hope for at least one gravity constant acceleration, which will bring us to light-speed\emdash or as close as possible\emdash in somewhere near \fs16 a \fs18 year. After that\emdash I don't know. Earth scientists are convinced that light-speed is the ultimate."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr smiled faintly. "Earth scientists have little practical experience in space-travel."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch continued as if he had not heard. "The point I was trying to make was, if we carry the extra mass of a second barge, can we reach that acceleration?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Certainly. More easily than with only one barge. You will have available the lift of both barges; they work on a positive-negative principle, like electric magnets."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch, a little at a loss, said, "Oh. I didn't know."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Pedratz the taffy-colored one, said, Two coils of welding tape, two hours, and two barges are one!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch rose to his feet, walked outside to check on the Calbyssinians. Arn, standing alone by the doorway, gave him an aggrieved glance. Barch bent to look at the wrist watch. "Your time's about up. I'll send out your relief."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He returned within, gave the Griffits instruction, went out with them, explained the wrist watch, then came back to the table, with the feeling of returning into a chess match. He said, "Before we weld the barges together, it might be \fs16 a \fs18 good idea to deck over the first barge, with the effect of doubling our floor space. Also, we'd better install whatever machinery we need\emdash the air conditioners, water condensers, the\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said, "Lekthwans use a single unit, \fs16 a \fs18 sustenator. Carbon dioxide and water vapor are extracted from the air; water, oxygen are produced, as well as basic food-stuff. The Klau presumably employ something similar."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch wondered if she might be deliberately flaunting her superior knowledge. Probably not, he decided wearily; it wouldn't occur to her as desirable. He looked for Tick. "Hey, Tick\emdash where do the Klau build spaceship sustenators?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick came over the locator, twisted the nob. "That's the growing plant for the shell down there\emdash the black and green. The final assembly is at Stalkoa-Skel, Magdkoa District, on the fourth tier. I once picked up a cargo for the space-works on Gdoa." He twisted the dial. "There, the red block."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 It would be easier, thought Barch, if I weren't so darned nervous. He studied the rock-colored hulk to his right. Kerbol had no more nerves than a lizard. Ahead was the thin crouched back of Tick, piloting the raft, completely at ease, making a chirping cricket sound with his lips.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked back over the side. They flew low; under and among a stream of barges, rafts, spheres and occasional flashing snapping objects like sheets of silver lightning. Overhead rose the massive, sooty towers of Magarak, crowding the sky, crowding the imagination. Even higher, feathery trusses flickered back and forth; smoke boiled and drifted. Colored flares fumed and dazzled; the air rolled with sound: clanging, chugging, roaring, hissing.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick flew confidently, almost happily, as if he were in a favorite stamping-ground. Barch shook his head in wonder, giving grudging respect to a brain which so casually encompassed and accepted this appalling bedlam.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The raft halted. Tick gestured with a hand like a monkey-paw. "That's it." They hung over what appeared to be a funnel of concentric terraces, vast as a crater, shining with leaden rings of light. A great black building, diamond-shaped, hung precariously over the gap, the sharp corner reaching to the center. Pillars of green light, like thick neon-tubes, rose from each of the steps into the building.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The diamond-shaped building expanded, the funnel opened out like a target. "Hold it!" cried Barch. "Are you going to land on that roof?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick waved his arm in a kind of lunatic light-hearted reassurance. "That's where the loaded barges come out; you want a loaded one> don't you?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "That's what we want," said Barch. "Drop down and be ready to land on one as soon as it's safe."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Safe?" Tick suddenly thought of his loss. "Nothing is safe, surety has fled; death rides one's shoulders like a brain-sucker." He turned to Barch. "Did you know that without the beach diagram, a man may not even die properly?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Watch that barge," said Barch unfeelingly. "It's coming out."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A barge slid up into the air, round black bosses making a polka-dot pattern in the hold. "Hell and damnation!" said Barch. "Do they ship an army corps to guard the things?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol squinted. "A dozen Lenape, six Bornghalese guards \emdash worse than the Podruods."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick slanted down. "Tell me when to land."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch yelled, "Pull up, you idiot! We can't kill all those men!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick turned the raft off to the side in injured silence. After a moment Barch said, "We'll have to wait for the next one. How long should that be?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick waved his arm. "I\b\scaps  \b0\scaps0 have no knowledge. Perhaps one hour, perhaps two. But we had better go back to the mountains; the project is impractical. Without my charm, I feel death close at my side."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We don't go back till we get one or two of those sustenators. We can't breathe five years on a barge-load of air."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "But you do not attack," complained Tick. "The barge comes out, you draw back, you hesitate. Better to go back to Palkwarkz Ztvo and sleep."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The next barge may have no guards on it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "All sustenator barges carry guards. They watch the Lenape, who have grown and modulated the sustenators, and who go along to fit them into the spaceship frames."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Oh," said Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick pointed. "Now here comes a barge to be loaded." He looked quickly at the locator. "Rust-orange\emdash out of Mem-pas Six, a Bornghaleze District."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said, "We'll board that barge. By the time it comes back out, it'll be loaded with what we want. Sustenators and Lenape brains. Quick!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick skidded the craft sidewise through the air; a trick Barch had never known the raft capable. It flipped over the rail, settled to the floor of the hold.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch jumped off, onto the solidity of the barge. "Come along, Tick. Kerbol, slide the raft up under the forward apron."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch ran lightly forward, slid open the dome. The pilot was a graceful maroon creature, handsome as a hero's mask; but, when he turned to look, Barch saw the four-point star in his eyes\emdash Bornghalese. No occasion for delicacy. Barch shot, pushed Tick into the pilot's seat. "Take over. Fly the barge down to the sideway, then stay put in the dome. \i Don't come out, don't say anything! \i0 When you get a full load, start out for Gdoa."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick nodded, reached down, detached the dead man's assignment card, fixed it to himself. Barch seized the dead Bornghalese, hesitated. If he dragged the body back into the hold, he might be seen from the black diamond building.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Kick him out," said Tick off-handedly. "Let him fall."\f1\fs24\par
\i\f0\fs18 Why not? \i0 thought Barch. He opened the front portal, shoved; the maroon body flapped down through the shadows like a demon-bird.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch turned to give last instructions to Tick, thought better of it. No need to instruct Tick in brass: that was carrying coals to Newcastle. He hastened back into the hold. The forward catwalk created a dark shelter; Kerbol had slid the raft below, raised it to press up against the overhead.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked around the hold for a hiding place, and perforce came back to the apron, under the forward catwalk. Where was Kerbol? Barch crouched in sudden cat-like caution, slunk forward, gun in hand.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Up here," rumbled a hoarse voice.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch ducked, looked up into the cross-bracing under the catwalk. "Oh." He swung himself up alongside, peered out through the lattice of metal lath. "I hope this turns out to be a good idea."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge grounded on a yielding floor; there was cessation to the near-soundless hum of the motors. The barge gave a lurch, slid into position, moved slowly along the slide-way. Lurid lights glowed on Barch's face; he turned his head, saw Kerbol huddled tightly in the corner as if impersonating \fs16 a \fs18 shadow.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A tall man yellow as a lemon, thin as a heron, wearing a conical green hat, leaped down into the barge, stalked thoughtfully back and forth, his eyes on the deck as if seeking \fs16 a \fs18 lost object. He bent, made a mark, stepped out with one stride of spidery leg.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The raft slid on. On one side gleamed high prismatic panes, from the other came a soft hum with forms and shapes moving, twitching, jerking, contracting.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A musical horn blast sounded; a second spidery man stepped into the hold, walked peering back and forth. He bent over the first man's mark, straightened, looked up. A tremendous black shape dropped with frightening suddenness, buffeting the air three feet from Barch's face, cutting off his view.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A moment passed. The great black shape snapped away like the flick of an eyelid, and now the hold was clear of all litter.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge slid placidly, as if floating in a quiet canal. Peering through the cracks, Barch saw a low portal ahead. The barge passed through into darkness.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\tx3418\f0\fs18 A tremendous hand seized Barch, banged him against the metal. A roar like a million whirlwinds rang in his ears. He seized the bracing, gripped for dear life against the pressure.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 The barge slid into light. Barch unfolded his bruised body, looked across to Kerbol. "Are you still there?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\tx3965\f0\fs18 Kerbol grunted. Barch fitted himself gingerly back against the angle struts, which now seemed cunningly designed to press into his aches.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Two men with long pony-faces, mottled white and brown skin, wearing hats like mushrooms, hopped down into the hold, waited. They looked up, reached. A black case hanging on a tube, like a berry on a stalk, dropped into the hold. The piebald men shoved it into a corner; the stalk snapped away.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 A minute passed, the raft drifted past a bank of blue, red and green lights. Then another sustenator dropped into the hold. Another rank of lights, another sustenator.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The struts ground into Barch's flesh, he shifted and twisted. Kerbol sat like a lump of putty, motionless. The hold gradually filled, the loaders backing stolidly toward the forward apron.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 After an interminable period, the hold was full. The barge slid on, around and up. Sudden vast bright space surrounded the barge. They had come out into a hall. The diamond-shaped building? Barch craned his neck, could see nothing but a high glowing ceiling.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He heard voices of a peculiar brazen timber that his skin recognized with instant contraction: Podruods. He saw massive red legs stalking around the catwalk; he thought he heard Tick's light rhythmical intonations. A moment later the deck sounded to the thud of new feet. Barch glimpsed a round yellow-brown face. Greenish-yellow splotches like grease paint surrounded eyes like balls of opal.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 One after another, perhaps a dozen, they jumped on rubbery legs into spaces between the sustenators, stood silent as bisque dolls.\f1\fs24\par
