\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Why do you want a sustenator?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Wait and see," said Barch shortly.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was further muttering. "And what will become of us?" came the question.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch grinned in spite of his irritation; they were disarmingly like a dozen little porkers, fearful of the trip to the market. "That all depends on whether the Klau catch us again. Right now you're escaped slaves."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Again they muttered among themselves. One jumped up on the catwalk, ran to the pilot's dome. Barch followed curiously. The fat man looked in at the locator, glanced at the broken chain, then, ignoring Barch, ran briskly back to his fellows. Barch watched with puzzlement.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol muttered, "That's the worst about the Lenape; you can do nothing to their satisfaction."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch stared. "Are those Lenape?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Kerbol grumbled and muttered.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch went slowly aft. He had visualized the Lenape as physically equivalent to their reputed mental ability.\f1\fs24\par
