\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 There was a moment's silence. Barch was the focus of a dozen curious stares. Then the first Lenape said, "A space voyage would be interminably long. The barges are insufficiently powered to generate second-order acceleration; you would float clumsily through first-order space, the deck pushing at your feet."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Five years in space is no worse than five years on Magarak. At the end of five years we're home. And maybe you can work out some system to give us more speed."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 The Lenape muttered nervously. "A grand concept. Is it practicable?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said angrily, "You don't act like you want to get home."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, no\emdash Lenau is life to us!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "A few months ago a dozen Lenape escaped Magarak."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "A simple affair for them; they merely bred a secret blister into the rind of the space-ship; that was all there was to it.... None of this painful fitting and piecing and improving."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Any fool can spear fish in a barrel." And Barch said in a disgusted voice, "Are you with me or not?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The little round men muttered anxiously together, all speaking at once. Barch failed to understand how communication of any sort was possible.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The foremost turned up his face. "We will work with you; there is no alternative."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch nodded in grim jocularity. "I thought you'd come around. Pass up those corpses; I'll drop them over the side now."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The next day Barch carried the locator back to the table in the hall, checked Palkwarkz Ztvo to assure himself that the two barges in Big Hole showed no tattletale sparks.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The head Lenape, whose name Barch had been unable to pronounce and so had called him "Porridge," came into the hall carrying a sheet of parchment. He marched across the room, lay the sheet triumphantly before Barch. "This," he said, "represents the needs incident to any such project as you envision."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch stared at the meaningless symbols. "Is each one of these marks something you need?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge bounced up and down jubilantly. "Yes. If you remember, I was of the opinion yesterday that the project was unrealistic."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said, "Let me have your pencil, or whatever it was you wrote with." Porridge handed him a flexible fiber. "Now, said Barch, "what is this?" He pointed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge brushed the first division with his finger. "Lavatory equipment, with spares. Shielded running lights, automatic pilot, and star-finder, communication equipment\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch sat listening in annoyance. "Porridge," he said finally, "imagine us in space with nothing in the barge but the sustenator, which produces our food and water."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Disagreeable," said Porridge.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Would we survive?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The question of survival is not the point under discussion."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Wrong. That's what I'm talking about. Every time I go out stealing things, I may or may not survive. And with me dead there's nobody else here with enough brains to get us off Magarak. So"\emdash Barch scratched a cross through the first division\emdash "out. Unnecessary. What is this?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 In a subdued voice Porridge said, "These are tools. Some I cannot translate, since they are very specialized. This is a hoist. This is a wire-splicer. These are various kinds of hammers, gauges, rotary buffers. All are quite necessary."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch sat back angrily. "What's wrong with you, Porridge? Do you think you're in a warehouse? We're out in the mountains. I thought Lenape were intelligent people. Why don't you ask for cushioned workbenches, automatic power-drills?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We did," said Porridge. "Right there."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch snorted. "You're worse than the Lekthwans\emdash you've got yourselves in a mental rut; you can't think anything but what someone's thought for the last million years. Haven't you ever heard of the word \i improvise?" \i0 Porridge screwed up his face.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Buffer\emdash what do you want a buffer for? Forget it! Hammers? Use a rock. Hoist? Run a sling under that little Klau raft." Barch crumpled the parchment in disgust. "I'll tell you what you're going to get: welding equipment, deck plates, and fuel for the engines. We'll probably have another barge or two before we're done; you can strip it of any spare parts you need."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge sat down heavily, kneaded his forehead. "You have a peculiar concept of comfortable space-travel."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'm not interested in comfort. Now you go back, start installing the sustenators, as many as the group of us will need. Also bring one down here, set it running; then we won't need to leave the cave for food, and we'll be safe from Klau hunters."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge departed. Barch, looking after him, saw Tick come diffidently into the room. "Tick," called Barch, "come over here."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Tick sidled up to the bench without much enthusiasm. Barch looked into his long sallow face. "What's the trouble?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I feel the pressure of my time. I sense the odor of death. If I once more owned the charm of my destiny, I would be secure when all else dissolves in fire and ruin."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch said thoughtfully. "From one point of view\emdash yes. But the charm is surely as effective in my possession as it is in yours. Now sit down, and tell me the best place to steal welding supplies."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Rain fell into Palkwarkz Ztvo, curtains and streamers gray as mourning crepe, hiding the twilight. The black mountain-side blurred and melted like dark sugar; black fronds pounded and dripped.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch, Tick and Kerbol had gone off in the raft an hour since. The Lenape sat grouped at the far table, muttering excitedly, tapping the table with fluttery little fingers, from time to time referring to calculations on a sheet of parchment. Lkandeli Szet, the sad-eyed musician in the embroidered black and green smock, sat drawing planget vibrations from his string-box; beside him squatted the Calbyssinians, blowing windy organ notes through their fingers; Chevrr, the hatchet-faced Splang, crouched as near to the fire as possible, mending a tear in his leggings; the light made moving pools of black along his deep-marked face. Flatface lay facedown on the bench while his women massaged his back; on the ground beside him a listless dice game was in progress. Only Pedratz displayed excitement, and this because he read omens in the fall of the dice.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr came quietly into the hall. She crossed to the entrance, wound through the S-shaped crevice, stood looking out into the rain. Darkness was absolute; there was nothing visible but the hissing vibration.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 She turned away from the entrance, looked around the hall. Two big tables, benches, shadowy walls, crackling fire. The plaintive sounds of Lkandeli Szet and the Calbyssinians. The smell of flesh and cooking and smoke. She closed her eyes. Outside were the dark mountains of Palkwarkz Ztvo and the black skies, heavy as an ocean. This was her place until dying-time, unless\emdash\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 But suppose Roy were killed tonight? Then she might despair indeed\emdash even though she had never permitted herself hope. But Roy Barch worked, Roy Barch effectuated, Roy Barch brought the possibility of escape within mental grasp. With Roy Barch dead, life became stagnant, squalid, with this cave her life and her death. Her eyes grew moist; it came before her mind, suddenly large, that only the optimism of Roy Barch made Palkwarkz Ztvo bearable.... A curious race, the Earthers. Young, only a few years removed from savagery, contaminated by the past, correspondingly exuberant and direct.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 She considered Barch's word \i dynamic. \i0 Odd that he should feel the essential characteristic of his culture so clearly. She wondered briefly about Earth: had the Klau infested it yet, \fs16 as \fs18 they had half a dozen other worlds? And what of Lekthwa? The longing grew too great, hope she could not allow herself; it would be self-torture even to encourage Roy. Hard on Roy, she thought. Roy gave the effort, the force; he was thanked by none. Barch, in the mind of the tribe, had become equivalent to hard work, when sitting beside the fire was easier, more pleasant.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 An hour passed, during which the Lenape rose in a body, trooped into Clet's old chamber and carefully laid themselves down to sleep.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Another hour went. The fire flickered and lapsed to coals. Komeitk Lelinar started listlessly toward her quarters.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Footsteps scraped and thudded outside the cave; Barch stood swaying in the entrance. Tick pushed past him, crouched by the fire. Barch's eyes swept the cave. "Where \fs16 is \fs18 everybody?" His voice was hoarse.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said, "They've gone to bed."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Bed!" Barch's voice cracked with emotion. "They go to bed while\emdash " He stopped.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Roy," said Komeitk Lelianr, "what's wrong with your arm?" Barch was clutching the region of his left side in a peculiar manner.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He came forward, sank down on a bench, said breathlessly to Tick, "Wake up the tribe. There's a barge outside. We've got to bury it in Big Hole."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Roy," said Komeitk Lelianr. "Your arm..." She felt suddenly weak in the knees.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "My arm and Kerbol," said Barch, "both back on the mudflats." She saw he was crying, tears of grief and exhaustion. Carefully she pulled the bloody rags away from the stump, and went a little dizzy. Faces peered over her shoulder, dull masks with eyes and nostrils wide, aroused to morbid excitement.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said weakly, "Don't stand here; get to work. Chevrr! Where's Chevrr?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Here." The hatchet-faced Splang came out of the shadows.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You know what to do.... Open up the wall, slide the barge in, close it up again. Take over for me; I'm all in."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The hall was empty, except for Barch and Komeitk Lelianr. Barch lay on the bench, talking at random. "We got it all in this load\emdash tools, welding tape, welder, deck sheeting.... There were Bornghalese on the dam. We waited to grab some lights, portable lights. They came running."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Lie still, Roy. Lie quiet."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "My left hand hurts\emdash in the palm\emdash and I don't have a left hand. It's mixed up in the mud with Kerbol.... Oh, what a sight...."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr tried to remember Lekthwan medicine, but the oddments and theories had no immediate bearing on a stump of an arm.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Pfluga, Flatface's second woman, too fat for work, came wheezing in to build up the fire. She peered at the arm. "And what will you do?" she asked Komeitk Lelianr.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I don't know."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Pfluga snorted. "There's only the one way." She thrust \fs16 a \fs18 heavy poker into the coals.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch fainted, and when the smell of burning flesh reached her nostrils, Komeitk Lelianr likewise fainted.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Pfluga snorted, sniffed, stirred the fire up under a pot of hot water. There would be calls for food and hot tea before the night was over.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch opened his eyes, reached out to pull himself to \fs16 a \fs18 sitting position, fumbled ineffectually with the air. He realized that he no longer had \fs16 a \fs18 left arm, propped himself awkwardly with his right. He looked at his bandage. Clean gray cloth. The stump ached, not unbearably.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr knelt beside him with a bowl of gruel. "How do you feel?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "As well as could be expected. What's been happening?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You've been sleeping for two days."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And what's been happening?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Three sustenators are welded in place. Today the decking is being put down. Tomorrow\emdash well\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Two days." Barch rubbed his chin. "Two days.... Help me up."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You'd better sit still."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I've got to think."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Can't you think where you are?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The Bornghalese saw us up along the dam. They know a barge is stolen, they know what's aboard. When the Brain finds out..."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A sensation like a cold draught played along Komeitk Lelianr's skin. She glanced uneasily toward the crevice.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch asked feverishly, "Have you checked the locator index for the Brain?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's not listed as the Brain," said Komeitk Lelianr uncertainly.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I can't understand why they wait so long," fretted Barch. "It's unnatural."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said soothingly, "Another few days and we should be ready to leave."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We need fuel\emdash\i accr. \i0 Tick calls it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "But you can't go out stealing again."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'll have to. Who else will go?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr had no answer. After a while Barch struggled to his feet. "I don't know why I should be so weak."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr took his elbow, steadied him. "You've lost a lot of blood."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch winced, closed his eyes as if to shut out a terrible vision. He muttered, "That rascal Tick, hiding, dodging, slinking. If he had stayed where I put him\emdash " He wiped at his forehead. "Well it's in the past; Kerbol's gone. But he was loyal. Kerbol stood by his guns, even when he died for it."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\par
\fs18 CHAPTER X \f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\par
\b\scaps\f0\fs18 Barch \b0\scaps0 made his way slowly up to Big Hole, where he leaned back against the wall, legs like wet rags. With gloomy satisfaction he listened to the sounds of activity. Barges One and Two sat side by side on the flat, with the four floodlights that had cost so much blood hanging overhead. Barge Three rested askew down at the far end, with the boxes and crates of three cargoes in between.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Barch calculated up into the regions above. Stalactites glittered and twinkled; the ceiling was gloomy, complex, Gothic \emdash but there seemed to be enough room, when the time came, to invert Barge two over Barge One. A delicate maneuver, but Tick had a completely sure touch.... As if Tick were telepathic, he looked up from where he squatted beside Pedratz, the welder, who was cutting pipe into stanchion lengths. He came bounding over the rocks like a cat. "Well?" asked Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "When will you give me my charm?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You'll get it as soon as we're out in space."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick tugged desperately at his braided sideburn. "Too late, too late." His voice rose to a neighing. "I feel the bulk of terror\emdash my brain aches, my knees are weak at wading through imagined blood."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch said in a cracked voice, "You'll ache all over if you don't stop that croaking. I've got your charm in my pocket; as long as I'm safe, it's safe. Think that over. Now go tell Porridge I want to talk to him."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick went crouch-backed across the stone floor; a moment later Porridge's round head pushed cautiously over the edge of Barge One. The opal eyes fixed on Barch a ruminative ten seconds, then he climbed up to the catwalk, backed down the ladder, trotted across the cave. "What do you want?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I want to talk with you about defending ourselves."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I know nothing about fighting. The Podruods are the great fighters." He started to turn away.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Just a moment," said Barch, grinning sourly. "We don't have any Podruods handy at the moment."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "True."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "From what you know of the Klau mind, how do you suppose they'll attack us?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I would assume that armored Podruod troops would be sent to kill us."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And suppose that failed?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge's eyes bulged thoughtfully. "They might send a monitor with torpedoes to break open the mountain. Or they might establish a cone of lethal radiation against the cave opening and then we would be trapped like mice in a shoe."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Come inside a minute," said Barch. "To send in troops, they have these alternatives. They can land a barge-load outside the valley, march them in, the same way the Klau come hunting. They can land a barge-load on this flat, in front of the cave. Or they can land them somewhere else in the valley, which is unlikely, because there are no other flat landing places within convenient distance."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge looked uninterestedly along the damp black mountainside, then pointed across the valley. "A barge might land on the knoll of that bluff."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Then the Podruods would have to climb down the steep slope and across those sharp rocks. However," said Barch, "that bluff would make a fine place to command the mouth of the cave. So that makes three areas we want to guard: the valley mouth, that bluff, and the flat here in front of the cave."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge fidgeted. "Yes, yes. On Lenau we would convert the ground to a gel with vibrators."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "This happens to be the Palkwarkz Ztvo," said Barch. "I'm going to fly a load of explosive over to that bluff and bury a few mines. Can you build me a long-range detonator?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "First, I must see the explosive."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Let's go back to Big Hole," said Barch. He gave a last look up and down the valley. "A gray day; notice how high and thin the clouds are? Klau come hunting on such days."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 They returned to Big Hole, went to the crates taken from Barge One. "Kerbol knew these explosives," said Barch, "I don't."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He pried open a crate, looked down at shiny gray bars lodged on a rack of rust-colored plastic. "This is super. Very powerful. We've got about sixty crates. Enough to blow up half Magarak."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He found a second box. "This is the stuff Kerbol used\emdash  abiloid. And this string is the fuse, or detonator."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yes, yes," said Porridge. "Quite common."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Can you work out a remote control?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge glanced down to the dome of Barge two. "There are instruments which could easily be adapted."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Good," said Barch. "Suppose you get at it right now."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Very well."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch watched Porridge march briskly off. He felt eyes upon him\emdash Tick's. When Barch turned his head, Tick looked away. Barch Watched Pedratz the welder a moment.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Each length of pipe made one stanchion, with about five feet of waste. The sight of the pile of five-foot lengths gave Barch an idea. He crossed the cave, tapped Pedratz's taffy-yellow shoulder. "Pedratz, seal off one end of about four of these." Barch pointed to the pipes.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Pedratz nodded, turned, prodded Tick with his toe. "Hoist four of those lengths into the dolly."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch's stump began to ache. He turned, left the Big Hole, started down the passage toward the hall. In the dark something sprang ferociously at him, threw him to the ground. Barch fell on his stump, felt the flesh squash, the blood squirt, lay in a daze. He felt nimble hands at his pouch, a hiss. Then there was a kick at the nape of his neck, a scuffle of footsteps.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch lay quietly, doing nothing more than existing. After a moment, with a whirling head, he gained his knees; his thoughts began to assume form again.... Tick? He clasped a hand into his pouch. No charm.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch ran limp-legged down into the hall. Komeitk Lelianr, seated at one of the tables, looked up at him in consternation. "Who came through here?" croaked Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tick..."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch ran to the crevice. Tick would make instinctively for the raft. If he escaped, if he added his story to what the Magarak Brain already knew ... Barch pulled out his gun. Tick was at the raft, tugging at the mooring line. He saw Barch, slid off into the forest, sprang into the trees like a monkey. Barch heard his shrill mocking laugh. "Too late, too late, you'll see me nevermore." And there was the rustle of branches, the clatter of black fronds.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch went to the raft, sank on it limply. He looked at the stump of his left arm; the gray cloth binding was sticky and dark. The bone ached intolerably.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He swung himself aboard the raft, untied the mooring line. Rising over the treetops, he coasted slanting down toward the river, the course Tick would presumably take. Underneath him the black fronds flapped and rasped, glistening like the scales of a great black fish. Tick was no more visible than if he had been an insect.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch lowered the raft to tree level, put his head over the side, listened. A soft crashing, not too far away. Barch manipulated the pedals; the raft slid like a shadow over the treetops. Barch stopped again. Silence. The sound might have been a wild animal. Directly below him Barch heard the crush of feet. He peered through the fronds, gun ready. But he didn't see Tick\emdash he saw a Podruod.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch froze. The Podruod, walking as stealthily as his weight and the ground would allow, vanished.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked swiftly around the sky. Was this the Klau attack he\\had expected? Down toward the valley came a sharp hoarse cry, a high-pitched babble in a voice Barch recognized as Tick's. A vibrant bugle call. Below him heavy footsteps pounded, the Podruod running toward the sounds. Barch relaxed. A hunt, and Tick was the quarry. Best take the raft back to the cave before the Klau hunter rounded the bluff.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch slid the raft into its accustomed spot, sat listening. The Podruod bugle calls sounded now up at the head of the valley. If Tick gained the wilderness of rocks at the foot of Mount Kebali, he stood a fair chance of escaping. But the trumpeting shifted, sounding ever louder. He's leading them to the cave, thought Barch. He limped painfully across the flat to the opening of the crevice, stood in the shadows.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Over the forest came the long black shape of the Klau raft, the Klau following the chase like a fox-hunter riding to the hounds. The raft came nearer. Barch could see the silhouette of the Klau.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick broke out of the forest, ran erratically along the edge of the flat, paused, looked with a passionate eagerness toward the cave. \i Afraid to come, afraid not to come, \i0 thought Barch. \i Well, give the poor devil a chance. \i0 He stepped out. "Hey, Tick." Tick looked up. "Come on."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick's face was a mask of indecision. His eyes ran fearfully around the clearing; then overhead came the Klau raft, long and black as a shark. Four Podruods burst out of the forest. Now Tick would have run for the cave but the Podruods cut him off. Barch stood back, silent, his gun ready. The Podruods came at Tick from four directions. Tick stood quiet, and Barch saw his frame grow rigid, his eyes start to pop from their sockets. \i Look out, Podruods, \i0 thought Barch.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tick ran forward, seemed to run right up the chest of the nearest Podruod. He caught the great red head, set his feet against the chest, performed a peculiar churning motion. The head twisted in three-quarters of a circle; the body fell like a pole. Tick sprang free, raced, dodged, cut in and out. The Podruods lumbered back and forth, and finally Tick was caught. Podruods fell on him from all sides; mastiffs tearing at a badger. Tick was down. The Podruods stepped back, their feet swung up, down, with sodden sounds. Barch turned away.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Behind him he felt the pressure of bodies, heard awed murmurings. "Quiet," whispered Barch. "Go up into Big Hole, tell them to be quiet."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Podruods at last stepped back, looked up at the raft. The Klau stretched lazily, sat up, stared around the flat. His gaze passed over the shadowed crevice; Barch felt the stab of the four-pronged red eyes. The eyes passed on; the bristling black head swung back to inspect the sky.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Black clouds were scudding across Mount Kebali. A few heavy drops of rain spattered on the leaves. The Podruods called up hoarsely, pointing to the clouds. The Klau ignored them. He waved his hand toward the upper valley. The Podruods shuffled sullenly into the forest.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The dead Podruod and the bloody tatter that had been Tick were left on the flat.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Rain started a tentative tattoo on the black fronds\emdash drops big as marbles. The Klau touched a button and a hood snapped over his head. He moved his foot; the raft slid down over the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch turned, pushed back into the hall. "That solves the Tick problem."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk \fs14 Lelianr \fs18 sat at the table, studiously intent at the locator\emdash poring over the index, checking into the viewer.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Barch stood by the fire, absent-mindedly watching the firelight and changing colors across her skin.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge bounded down the passage into the hall, trotted over to the fire, smelt appreciatively of the pot. Then, with a wary glance at Barch, he went to sit opposite Komeitk Lelianr.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 After a moment he spoke to her; she looked up, answered briefly. Porridge darted a glance over his shoulder at Barch, spoke at some length. Barch's curiosity could hold out no longer. He crossed the stone floor, seated himself beside Porridge. "How's the job coming?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Very well, very well indeed."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "When do you think you'll be ready?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge considered. "The deck is finished. Tomorrow we fix on the second barge. Next day we build on a double port. Then you can take the affair into space."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Is the double port necessary? I'd like to get away from here right away."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's indispensable in the event of repair to the drive gear and also when refueling becomes necessary."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Oh." Barch rubbed his chin. After a moment he said, "Tonight I'll go out after the fuel, and\emdash " he paused, glancing from Komeitk Lelianr back to Porridge. "What's the trouble?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Nothing, nothing whatever," said Porridge. He turned ostentatiously away. Komeitk Lelianr returned to the locator.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch asked her, "Any luck?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No. Nothing definite. I have a tentative idea."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The other Lenape came down from Big Hole, sat in a tight circle at the far bench. Porridge arose and joined them; an immediate clatter of voices arose.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said hesitantly, "Why are you so anxious to locate the Brain?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "When I find where it is I'll try to destroy it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Her eyes jerked up, met his. "Roy\emdash don't you think you should rest tonight?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Rest? I've got to get the fuel, \i accr, \i0 whatever it's called." He stood up, glanced around the room. Eyes flickered away from his, backs were half-turned Barch sat down. "What's wrong with everyone?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr's fingers moved nervously along the locator. "They think you're tired."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tired? Of course I'm tired! Why shouldn't I be tired, and everybody else for that matter? We can rest out in space."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said in a low voice, "They remember that Clet called you \i Crazy Man."\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch sat like an iron statue. "So everybody thinks I'm crazy ... I might have known. I saw Porridge giving me a couple of wall-eyed looks."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr said in a worried voice, "He can't understand why you want to steal \i accr \i0 when there's enough in the cave to last twenty years."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\i\f0\fs18 "Enough to last twenty years!"\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "So he says."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch slumped, exhaled a great breath. "Where?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "In Big Hole. In the crates. Kerbol called it super."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch's face twitched; he could not choose between laughing or yelling. He forced himself to be calm. "I never knew the stuff was \i accr. \i0 No one ever told me! Do you think I like ducking around through the fog, getting myself shot up?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No," said Komeitk Lelianr hurriedly. "No, no.... But why are you so anxious to destroy the Brain?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch, riding a heady wave of mingled anger and elation, said, "Think. By now the Brain surely has enough facts to conclude that fugitive slaves are stealing barge-loads of material."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "1 suppose so."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Any day we can expect to be attacked. If I can plant a bomb under the thing, I'll delay this attack a long time."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr frowned. "I don't think you realize the essential nature of Magarak or its organization."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "You've never said a truer word. I feel like a cat in a stamp-mill every time I take out that raft. Look at it this way. Would the Klau be disturbed if I blew up their Brain?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I should think so. It would be a most serious matter."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "What's bad for them is good for us. Call it diversionary tactics. That's simple enough, isn't it?" He took her silence for assent. "Do you think you can find the Brain?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I think I've found it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Good. And do you still think I'm crazy?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Her glance went to his left shoulder. "I'm not well-enough acquainted with the norm of your people to judge."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch rose to his feet. He said thickly, "About ten more minutes of double-talk, I actually would be crazy."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He went back to the fire. The hell with them all. Explaining motives was useless; his patterns didn't fit their minds. He put his hand to his gun; here was his explanation. He met Komeitk Lelianr's sudden alarmed stare, grimaced. Now she thinks I'm planning to run amok. Very well. No point in explaining anything. Give orders, see that they're obeyed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He strode across the room to the Lenape. There was a sudden silence; he felt the eyes of the entire tribe on his back.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Porridge," he said, "you think I'm crazy. That suits me; as long as you work, think anything you like. Tomorrow I want you to load Barge Three with cases of \i accr. \i0 I want you to rig a detonator on the bow, on each forward corner, to go off on contact. I want you to put a cut-out switch in the anti-collision mechanism, so I can disengage it whenever I want. Do you understand?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge blinked. "Clearly."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Good." Barch walked across the floor to the entrance, slipped out into the night.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The rain had stopped; the air was strangely calm for the Palkwarkz Ztvo. Barch crossed the clearing, wandered to his raft. For a\b\i\fs20  \b0\i0\fs18 moment he considered climbing aboard, raising up into the dark sky, riding through the night. But there was no guide-light set out, the locator was in the hall, and ground, and there it stood. Barch shot at the pilot, but the splinter whistled off the dome.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch hesitated a moment, then cautiously approached the weapon mounted on the stern. With one eye on the pilot he inspected it, tested the movement. It spun on a swivel. It was a strange pattern\emdash H-shaped with a long central bar, like a naval range-finder. The trigger was in an obvious position. The pilot was climbing out of the dome; Barch swung the H around, focused it as closely as possible, pressed home the trigger. There was a crackling sound; the control dome disappeared. The barge fell flat with a great squash and crush of air.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch turned to look at the bodies on the flat. A dozen or so squirmed, one or two crawled moaning along the stone. Barch swung the H, the crackling snapped out; a great oval spot on the flat was gouged out, seared, glossy.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A thousand feet above floated a raft with a crystal top. Barch peered through the sights. Two rafts. He moved the lever, the two merged. He pressed the trigger. The raft became a few flapping, falling pieces. No more targets. Nothing alive. Barch jumped down to the flat. He looked up to the cave mouth, saw nervous motion inside.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He picked his way among the bodies, slid along the crevice to the hall. The Lenape were huddled into an alcove, like puppies in a basket. "Get busy," snapped Barch. "If you can't fight, you can at least work."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He looked around the hall. Pedratz stood by a wall, his face bland and round as the full moon. "Get your equipment, see if you can cut loose that gun."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Lenape were trooping up the passage to Big Hole, pressing close together, making nervous motions with their hands. "Porridge," said Barch, "have you fixed up Barge Three as I told you?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "The work of a moment," said Porridge hastily.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "How much more time before we leave Magarak?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Difficult to say. The double port is not yet fabricated; the hull welding will be finished before the day is out."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Well, hurry up with Barge Three. If the Klau start to work on us seriously, we won't last very long. I think I can distract them."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Dangerous, dangerous."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Not if you fix everything exactly as I tell you to. Incidentally, you're coming with me. I can't pilot that barge."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Porridge sagged like a loose sack of meal. Without speaking he turned, hurried up the passage. Barch seated himself at the table across from where Komeitk Lelianr worked at the locator.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Come to anything definite?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Yes, I think so. On the index it's called \i Central Organ."\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked into the viewer, into the jungle of pastel shapes. The target ring encircled a small green square, surrounded by a blue mass shaped like an ink blot. To one side was a rusty-orange rectangle that seemed to quiver and jump as Barch looked at it; to the other a sprinkle of gray dots. Radiating away from the green square was a series of minute red capillaries, so faint as to be hardly noticable. "So that's the Brain."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Nothing else seems likely. I cannot be sure, of course."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Is it far?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's a third of the way around the planet, in the Central District."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Central District? More complicated than Quodaras?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Quodaras is a newer development, only a few hundred years old."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Oh. Well, it makes no particular difference."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was silence for a moment or so. Then, frowning into the viewer, she said, "Roy\emdash do you still think this plan of yours is feasible?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch made a disgusted sound. "The Klau just lost a barge-load of Podruods. Next time they'll send something heavier. We can't stand up under any serious attack. We've got to get their minds off us long enough to make ourselves scarce. We're walking along a precipice right now. And I've got work to do. I've got to see that there's enough raw material aboard for the sustenators. I've got to get Barge Three loaded with abiloid and a couple crates of \i accr."\i0\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 The day passed for Barch like the day before his execution, each second, each minute stretched far out, the hours paradoxically compressed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The work moved with exasperating slowness; Barch ducked back and forth into Big Hole, standing fretfully over the Lenape, convinced of their inefficiency but unable to comment because he did not understand what they were doing. He barked at the women who were carrying domestic utensils into the barge, raged at Flatface and the labor crew for spending their time gaping at the field of Podruod corpses instead of carrying aboard the logs of green timber they had cut.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Pedratz successfully cut loose the heavy weapon on the stem of the war-barge. Barch carried it slung under the raft to a niche just inside the cave mouth; from here he could command almost the whole of the valley. Suppose the Klau came while he was off on his final mission? He called to Chevrr, the dour Splang. "Come over here a minute."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Chevrr approached suspiciously. Barch explained the working of the gun to him, made Chevrr focus on several objects near and far to his satisfaction.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Now you stay up here. You're the guard. If you see the Klau coming, don't shoot, call for me. If I'm not here, use your own discretion."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Chevrr made a sound of acquiescence. Barch strode through the hall, climbed the passage into Big Hole.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge was standing beside Barge Three, looking up at the dome. "Porridge!" barked Barch. The Lenape turned his head; the round opal eyes met Barch's hot hazel eyes without expression. "When are you going to have that barge ready?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "It's all ready now."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Oh," said Barch. "The explosive aboard?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Everything."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Two cases of \i accr?"\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Correct. The rest is loaded aboard the space-hull."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Good. Now you're sure you've done what I wanted?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "There is a detonator fixed at each comer of the bow, connected to the cargo."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Good. I'll get the men to open out the cave, then we'll be off."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge made a vague whining sound. "I do not care to go. The journey is unnecessary."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch's face muscles twitched. He controlled his temper. "Show me how to operate the barge."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge jumped with great eagerness aboard. "It is very simple. Here is the speed. To go anywhere on the planet, set the target on the locator, throw this switch. This ball controls the barge when the locator-guide is not in operation." He spoke on, touching knobs and bars and finger-guides. Barch asked questions, sat in the seat, made sure he understood.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He climbed back down to the ground. "I'll go get the men to take down the wall; you bring the barge out through the hole."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch stood in the flat watching the rocks fall away from the opening. A black aperture appeared. Chevrr yelled down, a hoarse cry, "The Klau!"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\tx3245\f0\fs18 The men at the mouth to Big Hole froze; Barch looked up. Slipping down over Mount Kebali came a great black ship.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Hysterical wailing broke out everywhere around the cave\emdash loud sobs of mortal unabashed fear. "Shut up!" yelled Barch. "Get inside the cave!"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch took Chevrr's place at the gun, crouching behind the edge of the rock.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The ship cruised easily down the valley, past the flat, then rose over the narrow mouth, circled, came slowly back. The aperture into Big Hole was a shadow, facing away from the valley; it would hardly attract attention.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The ship once more passed before the flat. A great crackling filled the air; the flat jarred, shimmered. The crackling ceased. The wrecked barge, the Podruod corpses were gone. Barch's diaphragm convulsed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The crackling sounded again. The forest below the flat collapsed. The rock by Barch's face quivered. Behind, in the cave, the wailing recommenced. Barch growled over his shoulder, "Stop that racket!" He turned back. So far no harm done; they were shooting at random. Only a lucky shot could hurt them. He hoped the Klau commander would come to the same conclusion.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The ship passed almost overhead; Barch followed it in the gunsights. Perhaps the hull was immune to this relatively feeble piece; he held his fire.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The Klau commander acted as Barch had hoped. The ship circled down the valley once again, paused over the commanding bluff, settled slowly.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 In high excitement Barch ran into the cave. "Porridge! Where's Porridge?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 Komeitk Lelianr sitting at the table, pointed to an alcove. Barch ran over to find the Lenape wound together in a tight sweating ball. "Porridge, get out of there!" He reached in with his hand, tore the cluster of bodies apart. Porridge's red blinking face appeared. "Come out of there. Hurry!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge struggled clear.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Get to that remote-control box. When I give you the word\emdash let go number one. Understand?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge shuffled to the box on the back table, Barch returned to the crevice.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 The ship alighted softly on the bluff; instantly a ramp fell down, a corps of Podruods sprang out. Barch ducked back into the cave. "Now!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Violet light flashed through the crevice; an instant later the face of the cliff rang as if with the impact of shrapnel.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 Barch cautiously peered out across the valley. The bluff was gouged and splintered; in the valley below were the broken pieces of the warship.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch pushed back into the cave. "Porridge, where are you?" He ran across the room, caught the chunky shoulders. "Back to work! We count our time in minutes now." He swung around. "Ellen!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yes?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "I'm going now."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Roy\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "Don't argue with me. If I don't go, we have three or four hours of life ahead of us. They'll take us seriously now, they'll do the job right\emdash unless I get in the first lick."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "But, Roy, the ship must be almost ready..."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Keep Porridge busy until I get back. It's the only way to give us a few hours grace."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "And if you don't come back?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'll come back. But if I don't\emdash good-by."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Good-by."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch ran up the passage into the Big Hole. "Porridge, climb into that barge, back it out, push open a hole."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge wordlessly climbed into the dome. The stern of the barge brushed the wall; it fell open. The barge slid out into the air.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch stood a moment looking at the sky. Twilight was falling through the valley. Overhead the sky was mottled, like watered gray silk. The trees stood quiet and still; there was no sound. Barch's voice sounded loud. "Sure you won't come with me, Porridge?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge shuffled his feet. "I am needed to work."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Very well. Work hard."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We will be done soon."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch jumped into the little raft, slid it up to the catwalk behind the control dome. He looked into the hold, saw a satisfactory bulk of boxes. "Enough to do a little damage, eh, Porridge?" he called down jocularly.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Porridge threw up his hands, walked away.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked around the flat, looked up to the sky. In the cave mouth he saw a slim slight figure. Ellen? He waved. The shape vanished within.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch entered the control dome, seated himself in the unfamiliar seat Gingerly he put into practice Porridge's instructions. The barge rose vertically up. Barch twisted the locator index, looking into the viewer. There\emdash a green square on an irregular blue shape. But before he snapped the switch he manipulated the controls to get the feel of the barge. Up, down, sideways, ahead, turn. Nothing too difficult. Barch snapped the switch on the automatic pilot, pushed home the speed button, sat back.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge slipped like a shadow over Mount Kebali. Ahead was Quodaras District, a horizon-to-horizon blur of light. Below, the stone quarry showed a lonesome cluster of lights; how long ago it seemed that he and Kerbol had slid down to waylay Tick. Tick was dead, Kerbol was dead: fruitless, unsatisfactory, curtailed lives.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The stone quarry vanished astern like a pearl in the fog. Below Barch saw the glimmer of the Tchul Sea, the reflection from the far band of lights glistening on the surface.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge suddenly slipped sideways, steadied; Barch realized that now he moved in a traffic stream. Other barges floated past, alongside, over. Incurious faces showed dimly: faces with dead souls.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge flew over the glaring lights, the fiery pots, the churning arms, the incalculable shapes of Magarak.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Suddenly it occurred to him, how would he find his way home? There was no locator on the raft. He must remember to unclip it, take it with him.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 On the locator he gauged the progress of his voyage. Not yet half-way to Central Organ. Below, the buildings, the shapes, the moving arms, the fantastic fires, took on proportions more enormous than he had yet seen. The air reeked with acrid odors; the clatter and jangle of the processes reached up to astonish him. How could men survive such a nightmare?\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 And yet men did survive. Men had survived ice-ages, pestilences, wars, and now they survived Magarak. Human will-to-live approached the infinite.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He sank back into the seat, feeling strangely at peace. The chips were down; the hay was in the barn. His problems were behind him now; no more straining or worry. He either succeeded in his mission, returned to the cave, and left Magarak behind\emdash or he died.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 For a few minutes he lay drowsily back in the seat, then bestirred himself, checked distances in the locator. Two-thirds of the distance. He looked behind. Lights, swinging black shapes blurred in the distance. The same to all sides, all around the horizon. Without the locator he would be lost.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Minutes passed; Barch began to grow tense. Easy, he told himself. Either you do or you don't.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 At the extreme edge of the locator the green square became visible. Barch looked ahead. There\emdash that tall blocky tower, that irregular bluish shape.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch snapped off the locator, pulled the speed-control out to slow, dropped to a lower level. The tower soared above him, and Barch saw that it indeed glowed faintly green.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He started a circle, carefully threading the vertical avenues and lanes. Barges cut across his course; he caught the flash of startled faces. Easy, Barch, watch what you're doing. You don't want to meet any traffic cops now.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 At the foot of the tower, he saw a wide opening\emdash a ground-level landing deck.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He lowered the barge. A raft with a crystal dome drew alongside and Barch could see the pilot peering curiously in his direction. Barch paid no heed. The raft drifted reluctantly away.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 A vast sound like a siren rattled the air. Alarm? Danger signal? Barch raised in his seat, looked in all directions. Nothing untoward seemed under way.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The ground was close; the opening, lit by greenish-yellow light, was on his level. He flicked off the anti-collision circuit; started the barge toward the opening. Slowly, give him time to get clear. He watched a moment. Dead center. Good.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He opened the door, clambered back to his raft, climbed aboard. He stopped; my God, the locator! He ran back. The hole was very close. With his one hand he fumbled with the clips. One came loose, then the other. He caught it under his arm, sprinted back. The hole almost engulfed him. Aboard the raft, cast loose, away....\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The air bit into his face; he hunched down, urging the raft ahead. Faster, faster. Better lie flat. He fell forward on his face.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Light splattered the sky, painted the overcast dazzling violet-white. \i Ah, \i0 thought Barch, \i the explosion. Success! \i0 He clung to the raft. Faster, faster.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There came a great wind, lifting the raft like a chip on the surf, flinging it high and miles ahead. Barch glimpsed the great tower toppling, falling, smashing. There came a second explosion. Barch saw a blue blast, a tremendous fan-shaped flare, reaching instantaneously up, breaking through the overcast. Where the tower stood was a seething puddle of lava. The massive structures beside were mangled, torn awry, and as the great blue blast quietly died, the buildings glowed red and slumped.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The second air-wave caught Barch now, a milder, sharper impact, one which he heard as sound. Looking behind once more he wondered how many people had died, how many Klau, how many slaves. The Klau\emdash Barch shrugged. The slaves \emdash death was small loss to the slaves.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The raft was riding on an even keel, under control. Barch looked into the locator\emdash peered in astonishment. The viewer showed blackness, nothing. Barch shook it, pounded it to no avail.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 In sudden thought he looked behind. Did the Central Organ control the locator? In disgust and panic he tossed the mechanism behind him. He looked ahead. How had he come? Was this the right direction? All directions looked alike. There was no moon, no stars.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He looked over the side, searching for some half-noticed landmark.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The buildings bulged up, the myriad lights and vast motions were the same.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He looked behind. The tower was gone. But\emdash there was something subtly different about the approach. Barch got the raft around, circled to the left, looking toward the former tower. Building planes shifted, flares and fires took on different patterns. Now, this looked right. It was a gamble\emdash but the whole exploit had been a gamble. So far he had won.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch turned the raft away from the tower, set out at full speed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Now the minutes dragged where before they had sped. Surely he had not been so long over these monstrous shapes, with the bristling trusses like moth antenna. He kept on. The buildings seemed to diminish. By now he should be nearing Tchul Sea, but there was no Tchul Sea in sight. He had gone wrong. Now\emdash turn to the right or turn to the left? No. Straight ahead. With anxiety gnawing at him, one minute was like ten minutes. In every direction sprawled the man-hating bulk of Magarak.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He had come wrong. And yet\emdash a few more miles. And what was that vague blankness ahead? \i "Thalasse, thalasse!" \i0 had shouted Xenophon's myriad. "The seal" muttered Barch. "Good old Tchul Sea!"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The mud flats gleaming with murky phosphorescence like dead fish passed below; ahead was the mass of the Palamkum. It was almost like home, thought Barch. Now rest. His fingers relaxed. If they spent five years in space, he'd sleep the first year. Rest, sleep. No more driving, no more plotting and planning.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Below passed the lonely lights of the stone quarry; there was the ridge of Mount Kebali. He slid down the long slant into Palkwarkz Ztvo, noticing that there was grayness in the sky. Had the night passed so soon?\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was the blasted bluff, there the seared flat, there the black opening into Big Hole.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch landed the raft, jumped to the ground, ran up the hill toward the cave mouth. He whistled in case anyone should be on guard, but there was no challenge.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He reached the crevice, stopped short. He frowned. Where was the thin trickle of firelight that always glowed from the gap. Had they let the fire die? Had they extinguished the lamps?\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He stepped into the hall. The hearth glowed with dull coals. "Hey," Barch cried out. "Is everybody dead?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 No response, no whisper, no murmur, no slightest stir of sound. Barch ran up the passage into Big Hole. Gray light poured in through the opening. The double-barge was gone. Big Hole was empty.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch walked slowly to the opening. Wide. He looked up into the sky. The overcast came racing fast across Mount Kebali.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He returned to the hall, sat on the bench, held his hand to his head. The coals glowed, winked, and one by one died out. Barch sat in the cool silence.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Gray light seeped in through the crevice. Barch rose, went slowly outside. He banged the stump of his left arm on the stone and felt no pain. "Well," said Barch aloud, "so much for that."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\par
\fs18 CHAPTER XI \f1\fs24\par
\pard\sl-208\slmult0\qj\par
\b\scaps\f0\fs18 Barch \b0\scaps0 stood in the cave opening. Light rain fell slanting down the wind, so cold as to be near-sleet; perhaps the Magarak winter was beginning. Purple-gray overcast, heavy and twisted, scraped the black ridges. The notch at the mouth of the valley was blurred; the black fronds of the forest shook and rattled.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 He returned inside the cave, threw wood on the coals, watched the smolder start up into little flames, grow to \fs16 a \fs18 blaze.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 He turned away, and without reason climbed the passage into Big Hole. Watery gray light entered through the gap, twenty feet high, fifty feet wide; he could not possibly fill it in alone. He shrugged turned away, looked around the cavern.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He was still lord of vast properties\emdash the cargo of sustenators, less the three for the ship and one in the hall. There were crates of welding tape, the igniter, the cutting tools, spools of cable, a respectable pile of decking. The explosives were used up, all the \i accr \i0 had gone with the double-barge. Oddments, scrap, broken crates littered the uneven half of the floor. Nothing of value or immediate usefulness.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch started back down to the hall, then stopped. Something had to be done about the hole. With only one hand, piling up a wall of rocks was out of the question. But he could rig a makeshift screen, lashing up the deck-sheets with cable and maybe throwing a few branches against the outside for camouflage.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He returned to the hall, fed himself from the sustenator. The fire was warm, the rain hissed outside. He felt drowsy, torpid. He dozed for a few moments, then awoke with a start. Voices? Sweet woman-voices? Heart thumping like a hammer, he jumped up, peered around the hall. Nothing. He looked down the back passage, listened. Silence. He went out to the crevice, scanned the sky. The rain had become a heavy lashing torrent; the black fronds bowed, shivered; the forest sighed, wind moaned down the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch went up to Big Hole, worked furiously, half in the rain, half out. When he finished, a double row of panels hung across the hole, flapping and bumping. Not good, but better than nothing.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He went back to the hall, sat staring into the fire, and so the day passed.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 On the fourth morning, overcome by restlessness, he took up the raft. He landed precariously on the summit of Mount Kebali, stood looking out across Quodaras District. A smell of smoke hung in the air. Along the horizon Barch saw no less than twenty plumes of leaden vapor sweeping down the dank wind. As he watched a star-shaped flash of red fire burst up in the middle distance. Half a minute later, he felt a dull shock on his face, heard a rumble like thunder. Resisting the temptation to fly out over the city, Barch returned to the cave.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He spent half a day piling fronds of vegetation against the Big Hole panels. Backing off to inspect his work, he saw a barge sliding down into the valley.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch ran to the cave mouth, ducked behind his gun. He sighted through the finder; his hand went to the trigger.... He frowned, squinted. These were no Podruods; in fact, there were women standing at the rail as well as men. Fifty or sixty of them, a bedraggled lot, apparently all of the same race, with skin and features not unlike his own.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The barge settled to the flat. The stairs snapped out; a thin bald man with a shrewd round face jumped to the ground, followed by a tall youth with dark hair. Barch could hear the voices, but not the words.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 After a moment the rest of the passengers climbed down the ladder, stood looking uncertainly around the flat. The thin bald man spied Barch and the gun. He crouched. The others, following his gaze froze in consternation, their voices dwindled.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch called out in the Magarak pidgin-tongue, "Come up here where I can talk to you." The thin bald man and the dark-haired youth approached warily. "What brings you here?" Barch asked gruffly.\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 The thin man looked carefully behind Barch into the crevice. "You might call us fugitives. What about you?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-202\slmult0\f0\fs18 "The same."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 The dark-haired youth said quietly aside, "If wild men come any wilder, let's go back to Podinsiras where it's safe."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Might be he's a little off his rocker." Barch smiled bitterly. "I speak English myself." The newcomers stared at him.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Forget it," said Barch wearily. "So I am a wild man; so I am off my rocker." He nodded toward the barge. "All of you from Earth?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "We're what's left of Oakville, Iowa."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Never heard of it."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "The Klau dropped an army around town, herded us into their ship. This was two, three months ago. What's been going on since, we don't know; the slave revolt gave us a chance to bust loose."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Slave revolt?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Yep, started about four days ago. Somebody blew up the main headquarters with most of the Klau big shots. Ever since Magarak's been a madhouse."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "Well, well," said Barch. "And now what do you intend to do?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Well," said the thin man, "we figured we'd try to get back to Earth by hook or by crook. My name's Smith, by the way; this is my son Tim."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "I'm Roy Barch."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Smith gestured to the barge. "I understand these things run on the same principle as the spaceships\emdash grab at space and pull themselves along. Now if maybe we could make one of these air-tight\emdash "\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch sat down on a rock, ran his hand through his hair.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "What's the matter?" asked the thin man. "Did I say something wrong?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No," said Barch. "It's just that you've come to the right place. I organize these parties. I'm a specialist on them." He heaved a deep sigh. "You really want to leave Magarak?"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi-192\sl-202\slmult0\f0\fs18 "Naturally."\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\f0\fs18 "You're willing to work, take a few risks, maybe\emdash " Barch held up the stump of his left arm. "Yes!"\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi192\sl-245\slmult0\qj\f0\fs18 "All right, you've got a partner. Let's get busy. Take your barge around the corner. I'll let down the sheets and we'll slide it into the Big Hole."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch jumped to his feet. Smith and his son Tim backed away a little.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I'm harmless," said Barch. "Just anxious. This time I'll do it right."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Sure, sure," said Smith soothingly.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tonight we go out stealing. I know the routine cold. First we get the \i accr \i0 at the quarry. Next we go after Lenape. We've already got plenty of sustenators, but we do need a few Lenape. Something might go wrong with the inner workings en route and none of us could fix it."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Smith asked anxiously. "You feeling all right, son?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I feel fine," said Barch. "Let's get busy."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Double-Ark II rose into the twilight. Barch looked down into Palkwarkz Ztvo, hating the black forest, the black mountains, the interminable drizzle. And yet\emdash he looked along the length of the valley\emdash he had experienced a great deal here; he had accomplished much. "Wish I had a photograph of the place," he said over his shoulder to Tim.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tim clutched his arm. "Look."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch twisted sharply. Through the clouds flickered a dozen long dark shapes. The overcast swirled aside for an instant; the shapes showed as long torpedoes. The overcast closed; the shapes were gone.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Those weren't Klau ships," said Barch thoughtfully.\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No, I guess not."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "I thought I saw some kind of emblem on the first one."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tim hesitated. "I did too. But I think I was wrong. It couldn't be what I thought it was."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "United Nations emblem?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "But it couldn't be."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No. It couldn't be. Of course we were budding spaceships, but\emdash it's impossible."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 There was a knock on the door of Barch's room in the St. Francis Hotel. Barch looked up from the newspaper. "Who is it?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Tim Smith."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch rose to his feet. "If it's a reporter, \fs16 I'll \fs18 break your neck."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 He swung open the door. Tim Smith came in. "Just me."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Barch looked up and down the corridor, shut and locked the door. "I've been besieged the last couple days." He rapped the newspaper with the back of his hand. "I'd like to know how this stuff got out."\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 Tim Smith picked it up, read the headline: \i RAZING OF\i0  \i ENEMY WAR INDUSTRIES REACHES HALFWAY MARK.\i0\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "Is that what you're talking about?"\f1\fs24\par
\f0\fs18 "No," said Barch. "This feature article, by-lined Cyril Heats." He took the newspaper. "Listen:\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi288\sl240\slmult1\qj\i\f0\fs18 "The break-up of the Klau Empire under the pounding of the great Lenau-Lekthwan-Earth-Bakaima Coalition is now history and Earthmen will always glory in the fact that their fledgling Space-Navy dealt the first effective blow against the Klau slave-worlds.\i0\f1\fs24\par
\pard\fi202\sl-211\slmult0\qj\i\f0\fs18 "As a significant sidelight to this tremendous epoch in our history comes the news that one Roy Barch of San Francisco, captured by the Klau five years ago, can claim the honor of being the first Earthman to strike back at the Klau.\i0\f1\fs24\par
